[ECO "C45"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/28221186"]

{ Thank you for purchasing, and welcome to the course! Over the coming chapters, we'll be building up our understanding of the Scotch with the goal of developing a repertoire that will be suitable to play all the way from beginner through to advanced level.

I've been playing the Scotch almost all my life, so I may be a little biased, but in my view, the Scotch is one of the best openings you can go for at the non-professional level. It's also a weapon that you can employ against opponents of any level and is frequently seen at the elite Grandmaster level. } 1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4! { The beginning of the Scotch. White takes immediate action in the centre and, unlike in other popular openings like the Italian or the Ruy Lopez, White has an immediate and very strong threat of capturing the pawn on e5. } exd4 { Black should capture with the pawn. We'll spend quite a lot of time at the start of the course speaking about why other moves are not as good. One thing that makes the Scotch an amazing choice is that, depending on your level, you may find that Black doesn't play this move in anywhere from 30-50% of games. This means that you'll get a great position very early on a big chunk of the time! } 
4. Nxd4 } -- ( { This is the position that you'll have most often in the Scotch. And now, Black has a few choices to make, but none of them are without drawbacks. The most popular move online is } 4...Nxd4? { , which is a big mistake because our queen will be super powerful on d4.

The second most popular move is } ) ( 4...Bc5 { . This is the Classical Variation and is one of the best systems that Black can play. But it's going to lead to a lot of fun for us after } 5.Nb3 { and 6.Qe2, our intention being to go for a quick queenside castling and launch an attack against Black. White is scoring amazingly well in this line, typically >60% wins at the online level.

The third most popular move is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4...Nf6 . This is the Schmidt. Another solid choice, but it allows us to play 5.Nxc6 and damage their pawn structure. Later on in the middlegame, we'll try to take advantage of their weak pawns and go for a positional squeeze. The lines are quieter than in other systems, but it still contains plenty of razor-sharp lines.

After this, you'll see early queen moves a bunch: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4...Qf6 or 4...Qh4 . Here we'll go for a quick Nd4-b5 to hit Black's newly undefended pawn on c7. This usually will cost Black castling rights as they have to play the awkward ...Kd8. These lines are super fun as we often are willing to go down a pawn in exchange for huge attacking chances.

Finally, a respected and challenging system is the Malaniuk Variation @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4...Bb4+ . I think it's best to leave these chapters until the end. The theory is challenging but a lot of fun, as sometimes we'll be going for quiet positional play, but other times we'll be dancing with our king in exchange for being up a piece! Overall the lines are super promising for White, and here too, you can expect to get good results.

I hope you enjoy the course and have lots of success with this opening. I truly believe it's one of the best openings you can play at almost any level. One last piece of encouragement: I took a look at the database, and across 50 million games between players with an online rating of 1000-2000, White has scored better with the Scotch than with any other opening - including the Ruy Lopez or the Italian. So we're placing our trust in good hands!

Hopefully, this has served as a good introduction to the opening. In the next chapter, you can find the Repertoire Overview. [/course/179653/22] This is like the skeleton of the repertoire, giving you a quick bird's eye view of the major pathways of the opening and what we'll be recommending in this course.

After that, there is a chapter on How to Study [/course/179653/26] where I'll be recommending to you the best way of studying this course depending on your current playing strength.

Let's dive in! } )
*

