1. e4 } { This section is informational only. The idea behind it is to provide a quick overview of the major branches of the Scotch. } e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 exd4 ( { This is the start of the Scotch. In my view, the best move is by far } 3...exd4 { . Besides this move, at the higher levels, you'll only see } ) ( 3...d6 { as an alternative since most of the other ways of defending the pawn on e5 have a lot of drawbacks. } ) ( { • } 3...d6 { Covered in 'The Passive 3...d6' chapter. [/course/179653/4] We'll switch to Ruy Lopez positions with } 4.Bb5 { . From here, Black has two moves to respond to our threat of winning a pawn on e5. } 4...exd4 5.Nxd4 $16 { In this line, we'll end up taking on c6 damaging Black's structure. Later in the game, we'll push f2-f4, launching an attack in the centre and kingside.

The other line is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/ppp2ppp/2np4/1B2p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@ 4...Bd7 Breaking the pin. 5.Bxc6 Bxc6 6.Nc3 $16 Over the next few moves, we'll play Qd1-e2 and develop our dark-squared bishop. Then we'll castle queenside and launch a fast kingside attack. This position is unusual in that we have given Black the bishop pair, which we normally don't do. However, our strong central control coupled with a lack of open diagonals leaves White's position better. } ) ( { • } 3...Nf6?! { Countering against the e4-pawn is a bad idea as the tactics work out in White's favour. } 4.d5 { No knight jump is good for Black here. } 4...Ne7 { This retreat has been the most popular. } 5.Nxe5 Nxe4 { Both sides have grabbed one pawn, but the fact that it's White's move makes a big difference. } 6.Qe2! { Black has no good answer to the targeting of their knight. } 6...Nf6? { Most of the time, they've retreated here, which already allows White to win with } 7.d6! { next. See 'The Aggressive 3...Nf6' chapter. [/course/179653/5] } ) ( { • } 3...d5?! { Too aggressive. Black tries to mirror us, but the tactics work in White's favour. } 4.Nxe5! { The best capture. Now Black should play } 4...dxe4 { but most often plays } { 4...Nxe5 , which gives us an especially easy game. 5.dxe5 dxe4 6.Qxd8+ Kxd8 7.Nc3 $16 Black has lost castling rights, and the pawn on e4 is in trouble. Moves like Bc4, Bf4, O-O-O are likely next. White is almost winning.

The other line is @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/ppp2ppp/2n5/3pN3/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4...dxe4 5.Bb5 $16 The pin will lead to damaging Black's structure, and the e4-pawn will also be easy to target for us. White stands much better already. } ) ( { • } 3...Bd6?! { A bad move, blocking in Black's d-pawn and making their development problematic. } 4.c3 $16 { We build a strong centre and wait for Black to have to admit their mistake and move their bishop off the poor d6-square. Simple play from here for White with moves like Bd3 and O-O possible. Variation covered in 'Rare & Bad 3rd Moves' chapter. [/course/179653/3] } ) 
4. Nxd4 -- ( { Now we arrive at the biggest crossroads of the Scotch. Unlike on move 3, in this case Black has many good options available to them. Modern computers rate } 4...Nf6 { , } ) ( 4...Bc5 { and } ) ( 4...Qf6 { as the best. We'll continue in the next informational. } )
