1. e4 } { This section is informational only. The idea behind it, is to provide a quick overview of the major branches of the Scotch. It's designed with the intention to be read as a summary after you go through the whole course, but if you wish to take a look at it before you dive in there's no reason why that would be a bad idea! So, as you wish :) } e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 exd4 ( { This is the start of the Scotch. In my view, the best move is by far } 3...exd4 { . Besides this move, at the higher levels you'll only see } ) ( 3...d6 { as an alternative since most of the other ways of defending the pawn on } { e5 have a lot of drawbacks. } ) { After checking Black's early alternatives in our previous informational, let's see what we can face after this logical reply. } 
4. Nxd4 Bc5 ( { Now we arrive at the biggest crossroads of the Scotch. Unlike on move 3, in this case Black has many good options available to them. Modern computers rate } 4...Nf6 { , } ) ( 4...Bc5 { and } ) ( 4...Qf6 { as the best. } ) ( { This is the Classical Variation and the move you can expect to see most often. At the club level, it's about twice as popular as } 4...Nf6 { , although at the master level, both of these moves are similar in popularity. } ) ( { • } 4...Qf6 { This move is covered in the '4...Qf6 - Early Queen Moves 2' chapter. [/course/179653/10] This variation and the Steinitz ( } ) ( 4...Qh4 { ) both share one characteristic in common, and that is that the pawn on c7 is left undefended by Black. Our strategy will be the same in both cases: target the pawn with our knight! @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/pppp1ppp/2n2q2/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@ 5.Nb5 This line is interesting because if Black plays perfectly, we'll guide the game to a completely equal middlegame. But Black has a narrow path to walk, they need to first find 5...Bc5 , 6...Bb6, 7...Nge7, 8...Ba5 and 9...a6 to equalize! If they deviate at any point, they can end up worse or even losing! So in that sense, it's one of the most poisonous lines of the course, and we get to take very little risk. Expect most opponents to go wrong and give us good chances off the bat. } ) ( { • } 4...Nxd4?! { Covered in '4...Nxd4?' chapter. [/course/179653/7] This imprecise exchange is one of the most popular moves at the club level, so expect to see it a lot. It's not a good idea for Black, however, since our queen on d4 is very well-placed. } 5.Qxd4 { hitting g7. } 5...d6 6.Nc3 Nf6 7.Bf4 $16 { Next, White will castle queenside and look for a fast e4-e5 break to catch Black off-guard before they finish their development. White already stands much better. } ) ( { • } 4...Nge7?! { Covered via 'Rare 4th moves for Black' chapter. [/course/179653/8] Black's idea here is to replace their c6-knight with their king's knight. A drawback to this strategy is that they'll be left without any knight on their kingside, so this will leave them a bit more vulnerable to an attack. } 5.Nc3 Nxd4 6.Qxd4 Nc6 7.Qe3 Bb4 8.Bd2 $16 { Next, we'll play O-O-O before turning to attack towards the kingside. As usual, our strong central control gives us a much better position. This variation gives White easy play and great attacking chances. } ) ( { • } 4...Qh4?! { Covered in the 4...Qh4 chapter. [/course/179653/9] The Steinitz Variation has gone out of fashion for good reason, Black's approach has been shown by computers to be too greedy. Here we must be prepared to sacrifice a pawn and even accept a damaged structure. In return, we'll get a big lead in development and long-term attacking prospects against Black's vulnerable king. } 5.Nc3 Bb4 6.Be2! { The key move to remember. We let Black win the pawn on e4 to speed up our development. } 6...Qxe4 7.Ndb5 Bxc3+ 8.bxc3 { We take back with the pawn so that we can continue to threaten 9.Nxc7+, forcing Black's king to lose castling rights. } 8...Kd8 9.O-O $16 { White will attack Black for a long time here, and the good news is that modern computers believe that not only does White have compensation here, but is, in fact, doing a lot better! } ) ( { • } 4...Bb4+ { Covered in the last chapter [/course/179653/20] on The Malaniuk Variation. Black's idea here is to force us to play 5.c3 so that we don't have that square for our knight. } 5.c3 Bc5 6.Be3 Bb6 7.Nf5 { This is our major idea against the Malaniuk, looking to exchange Black's strong bishop and keep the d5-square under control. The idea is to do a positional squeeze of our opponents. From here, the main line goes } 7...Bxe3 { will give a stable positional advantage to White due to the extra space. After } 8.Nxe3 Nf6 9.f3 O-O 10.c4! { , White establishes a vice-like grip on the d5-square. This pawn configuration is known as the 'Maroczy bind', and the character of the game will be a positional one where we're looking to squeeze our opponents with the space advantage. One line that we need to be well-prepared for is the crazy gambit line [/course/179653/19] that we'll now show. @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/1bn5/5N2/4P3/2P1B3/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 4 7@@EndFEN@@ 7...g6!? The beginning of very aggressive intentions. 8.Bxb6 axb6 9.Ne3 Nf6 10.f3 O-O 11.c4 White is trying to stop ...d5. 11...d5!? But Black usually goes for it anyway! 12.cxd5 Nxe4 This is Black's aggressive idea. 13.fxe4 Qh4+ 14.Kd2 $16 From here, with best play, White will end up a piece to the good, and Black won't have enough compensation for it. But of course, it's never easy to play well when your king is dancing around, so it's definitely a line worth studying well to make sure we get good results here. } ) ( { • } 4...Nf6 { This is a major system, and you can find coverage spread out across the three chapters on the Schmidt variation. } 5.Nxc6 { We'll capture here, damaging Black's structure. } 5...bxc6 6.Nc3 Bb4 { Black will usually pin our knight, threatening to capture on e4. } 7.Bd3 d5 { Now they'll break in the centre and invite us to undouble their pawns. } 8.exd5 O-O!? { One strong variation that's been trendy in recent times (and for good reason) is this move. } 9.O-O Bg4! { This is Black's clever idea. Against the main line, we quickly play h2-h3, but by delaying the capture of the pawn on d5, Black doesn't give us time to play this move. If Black plays perfectly in this line, they can equalize, but in the chapter [/course/179653/16] called '7th &8th move sidelines' we show how easy it is for Black to go wrong and give us the better chances early in the middlegame. The good news about this line is that it doesn't come with much risk for White.

The main line is @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/p1p2ppp/2p2n2/3P4/1b6/2NB4/PPP2PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@ 8...cxd5 9.O-O O-O 10.h3 $16 . The more popular move historically has been 10.Bg5, but we're going for a different approach. Our plan is going to be to play 11.Qf3 and 12.Bf4. Sooner or later, Black will drop their dark-squared bishop back to d6 to challenge our strong piece. However, their inferior pawn structure will continue to be a problem in the long run. This line is all about outplaying our opponents positionally. Often we're looking to exchange queens since Black's fractured pawn structure gives us great chances in queenless middlegames and endgames. Overall I really like playing against the Schmidt as it's a safe approach for White that still offers many chances to win. } ) 
5. Nb3 { We're going to target Black's bishop. This is an aggressive approach against the Classical known as the Potter Variation. White's setup is definitely one where lots of tactics can appear on the board as we're going to go for queenside castling. } Bb6 
6. Qe2 d6 { This move is the most popular by a good margin. In the course itself, [/course/179653/15] we explore a lot of alternatives for Black on move 6. } ( { The main ones are } 6...Nge7 { , } ) ( 6...Nf6 { , } ) ( 6...Qf6 { and the tricky move } ) ( 6...a5! { which you can treat as an informational line since it's very rare at the club level. However, more advanced students of the course should definitely pay special attention to that one. } ) 
7. Nc3 Nf6 
8. Be3 } { White clears the queenside minor pieces off the first rank and at the same time challenges Black's strong bishop on b6. } O-O 
9. O-O-O { We get an opposite side castling position where our plan is quite simple: push our kingside pawns! } Re8 } ( { Black has many different approaches they can take, such as exchanging dark-squared bishops or playing } 9...Be6 { . This move, however, is the most popular, targeting the pawn on e4. } ) 
10. f3 Be6 
11. Kb1 $16  } { A useful move that we'll often play, stepping our king off the somewhat exposed c1-h6 diagonal. Now we're ready to push with 12.g4 next. Overall, these lines are really good for White because our attack is stronger than Black's, and we have a nice space advantage in the centre as well as mostly quite easy logical play. Black, on the other hand, has to make tough decisions at every turn. }-- ( { For instance, sometimes they take on e3 when it's not good, and often they even play the bad move } 11...Bxb3 { giving us their strong e6-bishop. It's just one of those spots for Black where it's hard for them to find the right plan, while for us, it's very straightforward as we have a typical attack that we can build on the kingside.

With this, we conclude the mindmap! Hopefully, it's been helpful for you to revise the course. And perhaps it will be a useful tool if you ever want to quickly review the main ideas of the course without diving into the nitty-gritty of the theory! } )
