[Event "Starting Out: The Scotch"]
[White "How to Study the Course"]
[Black "How to Study the Course"]
[Date "2023.07.18"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/28747551"]

1. -- { Since this course is intended for a wide rating range, it may be useful to give a quick guide on how I recommend working your way through the course:

Rating of student (0-1700)

• Quickstarter [/course/179653/21] to get a barebones repertoire centred around the most popular lines and enable you to start playing the opening right away.

• 'Third moves for Black' [/course/179653/2] and 'Fourth moves for Black' [/course/179653/6] to build a good overview of the major branches of theory.

• The 4...Nxd4?! chapter. [/course/179653/7] This is a bad move, but you'll face it a lot at the lower levels, so it's good to know how to make full use of your opponent's mistake.

• The 4...Qh4 chapter [/course/179653/9] as it's an aggressive line where it's easy to go wrong if you don't know the theory.

After this, I would work progressively through the remaining chapters, with a special focus on the Classical Variation (as that's about twice as popular as the Schmidt at the club level). You can leave the Malaniuk chapters for last, as the theory is challenging, but it's a pretty rare guest.

Also, you may occasionally find a comment such as 'advanced students may wish to study this position further'. I would recommend not worrying about these on your first run-through of the course, so as to avoid getting overwhelmed and staying focused on learning the fundamentals well.

Finally, the Tactics & Model Games [/course/179653/25] chapters will help you to build a good feel for the opening, and these are good to complete after studying the theory.

Rating of student (1700+)

• The rare moves chapters will take on less importance the higher your rating as you will probably be able to instinctively find good moves against these bad systems. My focus would be on:

1. The passive 3...d6 system [/course/179653/4] (second most popular system after 3...exd4)

2. 4...Qh4 [/course/179653/9] & 4...Qf6 [/course/179653/10] (these demand precise replies if you want to get an edge)

3. The Classical Variation (the most popular of the major systems)

4. The Schmidt (paying special attention to the tricky 9...Bg4!? line in the chapter [/course/179653/16] on 7th & 8th Move Sidelines)

5. The Malaniuk (paying special attention to the ultra-sharp 7...g6 line [/course/179653/19]) You will also benefit from the Tactics & Model Games chapters, especially if you are new to the Scotch. } } *

