1. e4 } e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 d6 { This is Black's most popular sideline so it pays to know what to do against it. There's a few different approaches we could take here. We'll be playing in Ruy Lopez fashion as it leads to simple play and a nice edge for White. } 
4. Bb5 } { We're threatening to capture the pawn on } { e5 now that Black's knight is pinned. Black can meet this move in one of two ways: { 4...exd4 , or 4...Bd7 . } Bd7?! ( { This move is almost as popular as } 4...exd4 { . It's been played by Grandmasters over the years, usually via the Ruy Lopez move order, but modern computers feel that Black is in some trouble here, and tournament results support that as White is scoring great here. } ) 
5. Bxc6 { Removing the defender of e5. } Bxc6 
6. Nc3 } { Protecting our pawn on e4. Now we're threatening to capture on e5. Black has a few options to choose from here. }exd4 ( { Let's take a look at Black's most popular reply: } 6...exd4 { . In the course itself, we also address the alternative of } ) ( 6...Nf6 { . } ) 
7. Nxd4 { We take back with the knight, putting pressure on the bishop on c6. } Bd7 { It makes sense to drop the bishop back, not only does Black no longer have to worry about it being captured, but also ideas for White involving pushing our b-pawn to b5 are now less effective. That said, White has a nice space advantage in the centre and easy development, so we should be very happy here. } 
8. Qe2 { I like this move, keeping our options of castling on the queenside open for now. } Nf6 ( { Sometimes Black will start with } 8...Be7 { and only on the next move play 9...Nf6. } ) 
9. Bf4 $16  } { Our bishop takes up an active square along the long diagonal. It stands better here than on g5 since we actually want to castle queenside, and then push up our g-pawn in the future. White stands a lot better already, as Black's pieces are a bit too passive. } *

