1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 d6 { This is Black's most popular sideline so it pays to know what to do against it. There's a few different approaches we could take here. We'll be playing in Ruy Lopez fashion as it leads to simple play and a nice edge for White. } 
4. Bb5 } { We're threatening to capture the pawn on } { e5 now that Black's knight is pinned. Black can meet this move in one of two ways: { 4...exd4 , or 4...Bd7 . } exd4 { Black makes a small concession in the centre by trading off their most central pawn, but now they no longer have to worry about our threat of capturing it. } 
5. Nxd4 } { Black has to deal with our threat of 6.Nxc6. } Bd7 } ( { It makes sense for Black to block in this way rather than defend with a move like } 5...Nge7 { since their knight is going to be better placed on the more active f6-square. } ) 
6. Nc3 { You could also castle instead, it will probably just transpose. We are in that stage of the opening where both sides are playing natural moves to finish their development. } Nxd4?! { Most of the time Black wants to avoid their pawns being doubled, and so they capture here. However, this leads to our queen being very well-placed on d4. } 
7. Bxd7+ { Taking first is slightly better than letting them take us, since if we do that our knight ends up on the odd-looking b5-square. } Qxd7 
8. Qxd4 Nf6 
9. Bg5 { Developing with tempo makes sense here, though many good moves exist for White. } Be7 
10. O-O-O $16  } { White is doing really well here, with ideas of either 11.e5 or pushing the kingside pawns. Black has less space and no clear plan. } *

