1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 Nf6 { With this move Black counter-attacks the pawn on e4 hoping that the complications will work out in their favour. Fortunately for us, they work to White's advantage! Let's take a look. } 
4. d5!  we cover all of Black's possible knight jumps, but here we'll focus on the most popular reply only. } Ne7 { Black's knight is looking to find a new home on g6 in the future while keeping the e-file somewhat closed, which they may be hoping will help in the event the e4 and e5 pawns come off the board.

However, this move has one very big drawback: the vision of our opponent's bishop on f8 is cut off, and as a result, the d6-square is not well-controlled by Black. We will soon see the importance of this detail! } 
5. Nxe5 Nxe4 ( { Black levels the score, but their knight on e4 is very exposed, while their knight on e7 hinders their development. } 5...d6? { You'll see this a lot, but as in other similar instances in the chapter,  [/course/179653/5] we have a strong reply. } 6.Bb5+! { Black has to block the check, and because of this, they are left without any time to win the pawn on e4. } ) 
6. Qe2 Nf6? { Most of the time Black has dropped the knight back to f6, but here we have a beautiful way to win on the spot! } 
7. d6! { We will see the point behind this move very soon. } cxd6 { Black has to take the pawn since any knight move would allow us to play 8.Nc6+ winning their queen. } 
8. Nc4! } { This is the clever point. Black has no way to hang onto the d6-pawn. And in fact, we're threatening 9.Nxd6 next, which would be a pretty smothered mate. } Qc7 { Black can only hang onto the pawn for one more move. } 
9. Bf4+- } { White is completely winning, as we are going to play 10.Nxd6+ on the next move and capture on f7 and h8 in sequence! } *

