1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 d5?! { Black plays aggressively in the centre, mirroring our strategy. The good news is that as long as we capture the right pawn in the right way, we'll grab a big advantage right off the bat! } 
4. Nxe5! } dxe4 ( { This is the best way to capture. White is up a pawn, but Black can recover it. They have a choice of whether to first exchange knights or to play } 4...dxe4 { immediately. } ) { This is the lesser evil. At least here Black's castling rights are not taken away. That said, Black is unable to come close to equalizing. } 
5. Bb5! { Developing while threatening to capture on c6. } Bd7 { Black usually takes time to defend their knight on c6. } 
6. Bxc6 ( { Whatever you do, make sure to avoid } 6.O-O?? { since after } 6...Nxe5! { Black wins a piece. I like to capture twice on c6 to mess up their pawn structure. } ) Bxc6 
7. O-O { We could also have taken on c6 immediately, but the bishop is not going away any time soon! } Bd6 
8. Nxc6 { Now is a good time to capture since our knight was threatened. } bxc6 
9. Qe2 $16  } { White has a better pawn structure, and the pressure on e4 is very problematic for Black since we have moves like Nd2 or Nc3 followed by Re1 coming up. } *

[Event "Starting Out: The Scotch"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Rare & Bad 3rd Moves: 3...d5 #2"]
[Date "2023.07.18"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C44"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/28416380"]

1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 d5?! { Black plays aggressively in the centre, mirroring our strategy. The good news is that as long as we capture the right pawn in the right way, we'll grab a big advantage right off the bat! } 
4. Nxe5! Nxe5 ( { This is the best way to capture. White is up a pawn, but Black can recover it. They have a choice of whether to first exchange knights or to play } 4...dxe4 { immediately. } ) 
5. dxe5 } dxe4 { Recovering the pawn is probably best. } 
6. Qxd8+ { White forces Black to lose castling rights, and on top of this the king on d8 is very vulnerable along the open d-file. } Kxd8 
7. Nc3 } { Targeting the e4-pawn. } Bf5 
8. Bc4 } { Targeting the f7-pawn. } f6 { Usually, Black has played in this fashion, saving their pawn and also challenging the e5-pawn. The problem for Black is that such offers of exchanging pawns will create more open lines, and White is the one that is well-placed to take advantage of this. } 
9. Bf4+- } { Simple and strong. Objectively it's no exaggeration to say that White is winning since we'll castle queenside next, gaining more time against Black's king, while the e4-pawn should fall in the near future. Additionally, we'll be able to generate a very strong attack against their king even in the absence of queens on the board. } *

[Event "Starting Out: The Scotch"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Early Queen Moves - 4...Qh4"]
[Date "2023.07.18"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C45"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/28416381"]


1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 exd4 { This is the move you will see the majority of the time. It's the clear best move. For an in-depth understanding of why, you can refer to the 'Third Moves for Black' chapter. [/course/179653/2] There, we explain the pros and cons of all of Black's replies that will be covered in this course. } ( { Depending on your level you'll see } 3...exd4 { more or less often. In online games between players rated 0-1400, Black plays it around 60% of the time. While in games between players rated 2000+ we see it played a little over 90% of the time. There's a clear trend here! The higher the rating of your opponent, the more likely that they'll know that } ) ( 3...exd4 { is best and play it automatically. But if you are playing mostly club-level opponents, you can probably expect to play against sidelines about 35-40% of the time. This is one of the great things about playing the Scotch, since for the most part, the sidelines will offer us a great opportunity to get an advantage right off the bat! } ) 
4. Nxd4  In the Quickstarter, we'll go over the most popular moves, which at the club level will be in this order: }Qh4?! } ( 4...Nxd4?! { A bad idea, allowing us to develop our queen to the powerful d4-square. We're going to face this move a lot, and that's a great thing! } { 4...Bc5 The Classical Variation. One of Black's strong options, developing a piece and hitting our knight on d4. }{ 4...Nf6 The Schmidt - Another solid and popular approach, developing the knight and striking at our e4-pawn. }{ 4...Qf6 An unusual approach, striking at our d4-knight and also putting some pressure against f2. }{ 4...Qh4 The Steinitz variation - similar to the previous line but an even more aggressive post of the queen. This one is actually Black's best scoring line at the club level, so we should be careful! But the good news is White is doing really well here if they know a powerful gambit line that we'll be covering here! }{ 4...Bb4+ The Malaniuk variation. A rare guest at the club level but a popular guest at the master level. The idea behind giving the check is to invite us to play 5.c3 when we will no longer have that square for our knight. The theory can be quite challenging, and I would suggest students rated below 2000 to leave the study of these chapters for the end. }) { This is known as the Steinitz Variation. Black immediately targets our pawn and, at the same time, pressures the f2-point. This means that if Black follows up with ...Bc5, we have to be careful to avoid getting checkmated early!

That said, this move is not especially good because Black's queen steps out prematurely. Importantly, the queen no longer protects the c7-pawn from h4, and, since we have a knight on d4, we can, at the right moment, try to play Nd4-Nb5 and cause Black some problems. } 
5. Nc3 { For now, we continue our development and protect the e4-pawn. } Bb4 { This is the only good move for Black and the logical follow-up to 4...Qh4. This is because, with our knight pinned, Black is now threatening to play ...Qxe4+. This moment is the most important, since, in order to get an advantage, we must remember to play one move and one move only. Everything else gives Black a good game or even an advantage. } 
6. Be2! { A great move! White recognises that it's more trouble than it's worth to try to hang onto the pawn on e4 and instead, we let Black capture the pawn but in exchange build up a big initiative. } Bxc3+ { More often than not Black will take here on c3 first, so it's what we're focusing on in the Quickstarter. } ( 6...Qxe4 { is the better choice, which is covered in depth [/variation/28221263/#/6/b] in the full course. } ) 
7. bxc3 Qxe4 
8. O-O! { Although we're down a pawn and have a worse structure, our huge development lead and the strong bishop pair mean that Black is in a lot of trouble. } Nxd4 { Black gets rid of our knight to avoid Nb5 ideas, but at the same time, they give us the opportunity to undouble our c-pawns. } 
9. cxd4 Ne7 { Black tries to keep the e-file closed as much as possible. } 
10. Re1 } Qh4 ( { But unfortunately for them, we are in time! This is the most precise move for a subtle reason that can be seen if Black castles now: } 10...O-O? { runs into } 11.Bg4!+- { winning a piece. Note: going to the g4 square is important as we cut off the possibility of Black playing ...Qh4 from where the queen would be defending the knight on e7. } { This is why we play 10.Re1! rather than something like 10.Bf3? first. } ) { The most stubborn defense. Black anticipates our Bg4 idea and keeps contact with the knight on e7 before preparing to castle on the next move. } 
11. g3 Qf6 { Black stays protecting the knight. The goal for them is to be able to castle. } 
12. h4 $16  } { White has so many threats that it's very hard for Black to deal with all of them. And Black also has a lot of problems finishing their queenside development, leaving us with a much better position. } *


