4. Nxd4 { From here, Black has a lot of options. We'll explain these in detail in the 'Fourth Moves for Black' chapter. [/course/179653/6] In the Quickstarter, we'll go over the most popular moves, which at the club level will be in this order: }Qf6 ( 4...Nxd4?! { A bad idea, allowing us to develop our queen to the powerful d4-square. We're going to face this move a lot, and that's a great thing! } { 4...Bc5 The Classical Variation. One of Black's strong options, developing a piece and hitting our knight on d4. }{ 4...Nf6 The Schmidt - Another solid and popular approach, developing the knight and striking at our e4-pawn. }{ 4...Qf6 An unusual approach, striking at our d4-knight and also putting some pressure against f2. }{ 4...Qh4 The Steinitz variation - similar to the previous line but an even more aggressive post of the queen. This one is actually Black's best scoring line at the club level, so we should be careful! But the good news is White is doing really well here if they know a powerful gambit line that we'll be covering here! }{ 4...Bb4+ The Malaniuk variation. A rare guest at the club level but a popular guest at the master level. The idea behind giving the check is to invite us to play 5.c3 when we will no longer have that square for our knight. The theory can be quite challenging, and I would suggest students rated below 2000 to leave the study of these chapters for the end. }) { With this move Black targets our knight on d4, but the problem with these early queen moves for Black is that the pawn on c7 is left undefended. } 
5. Nb5! } } ( { The only good move for Black, ignoring the threat and creating an even bigger threat of their own against our f2-pawn. } 5...Bd6? { An example of Black players going wrong quickly is this move. } 6.Nxd6++- { Not only do we grab the bishop pair, but we also ruin Black's pawn structure. } ) 
6. Qe2 ( { We defend the f2-pawn while not blocking off our dark-squared bishop on c1, as would happen if we played a move like } 6.Qd2 { . } ) ( { We must avoid capturing the pawn: } 6.Nxc7+?? Kd8 { and White is losing since Black threatens both } 7.-- Kxc7 { and } { 7...Qxf2 mate. } ) Bb6 { Black drops the bishop back to defend the c7-pawn. } 
7. N1c3 } { White is threatening Nd5 so Black must address this. } a6? { A common blunder. } 
8. Nd5! } Ba5+ { The most resilient move, saving the bishop from capture by gaining time with a check. } 
9. c3 Qd8 { Defending the c7-pawn. } 
10. Na3 $16  } { White is much better here, threatening moves like Nc4. Also, we don't have to spend time moving our queen here because we can finish our kingside development with 11.g3 and 12.Bg2. Positionally speaking, we have a really nice grip in the centre. } *


