3. d4 exd4 { This is the move you will see the majority of the time. It's the clear best move. For an in-depth understanding of why, you can refer to the 'Third Moves for Black' chapter. [/course/179653/2] There, we explain the pros and cons of all of Black's replies that will be covered in this course. } ( { Depending on your level you'll see } 3...exd4 { more or less often. In online games between players rated 0-1400, Black plays it around 60% of the time. While in games between players rated 2000+ we see it played a little over 90% of the time. There's a clear trend here! The higher the rating of your opponent, the more likely that they'll know that } ) ( 3...exd4 { is best and play it automatically. But if you are playing mostly club-level opponents, you can probably expect to play against sidelines about 35-40% of the time. This is one of the great things about playing the Scotch, since for the most part, the sidelines will offer us a great opportunity to get an advantage right off the bat! } ) 
4. Nxd4 { From here, Black has a lot of options. We'll explain these in detail in the 'Fourth Moves for Black' chapter. [/course/179653/6] In the Quickstarter, we'll go over the most popular moves, which at the club level will be in this order: }Bc5 ( 4...Nxd4?! { A bad idea, allowing us to develop our queen to the powerful d4-square. We're going to face this move a lot, and that's a great thing! } { 4...Bc5 The Classical Variation. One of Black's strong options, developing a piece and hitting our knight on d4. }{ 4...Nf6 The Schmidt - Another solid and popular approach, developing the knight and striking at our e4-pawn. }{ 4...Qf6 An unusual approach, striking at our d4-knight and also putting some pressure against f2. }{ 4...Qh4 The Steinitz variation - similar to the previous line but an even more aggressive post of the queen. This one is actually Black's best scoring line at the club level, so we should be careful! But the good news is White is doing really well here if they know a powerful gambit line that we'll be covering here! }{ 4...Bb4+ The Malaniuk variation. A rare guest at the club level but a popular guest at the master level. The idea behind giving the check is to invite us to play 5.c3 when we will no longer have that square for our knight. The theory can be quite challenging, and I would suggest students rated below 2000 to leave the study of these chapters for the end. }) 
5. Nb3 } } ( { This is the Classical Variation and has withstood the test of time. Alongside 4...Nf6, these two moves represent the gold standard for how Black deals with the Scotch and will be where the majority of your battles take place. White can respond to this move in a variety of ways, namely three main ways.

• The first is to play } 5.Be3 { supporting the knight.

• The second is to play } ) ( 5.Nxc6 { seeking to cause some damage to Black's structure.

• The last is our choice for this repertoire, to drop the knight back to b3 and target Black's dark-squared bishop. There are two reasons why we're choosing this approach:

1. The theory is less developed here, so there's less for us to study and more likely that our opponents will not respond correctly.

2. This allows us to set ourselves up way more aggressively, and in general, at the club level, players are not so good at handling being attacked! } ) { Saving our knight and targeting Black's bishop. This is known as the Potter Variation. } Bb6 { This is the move you will encounter almost always. Black saves their bishop from attack and keeps it on the long g1-a7 diagonal. } 
6. Qe2 { We go for this unusual-looking aggressive setup! There's a few ideas behind this move:

1. Protect the f2-pawn, which can be a little vulnerable given Black's bishop on b6.

2. Cover the e3-square; this is useful since we in some situations will play Bc1-e3 to challenge Black's best piece.

3. Begin clearing pieces from the queenside in order to be able to castle there and get an attacking game with opposite-side castling. }Nge7 } ( { Black has a lot of replies from here. In the Quickstarter, we're going to be looking at the three most popular moves: } 6...d6 { , } ) ( 6...Nge7 { , and } ) ( 6...Nf6 { . } ) { Black steps their knight out via e7 instead of the more natural f6-square. While this square is not as active, it does have a few possible benefits like the fact that now White can't easily pin the knight with a move like 7.Bg5. Also, Black can play the ...f5 pawn break in the future in some lines. } 
7. Nc3 } ( { It's good to begin with this and not, say, } 7.Be3 { since if we do this Black could break in the centre immediately with } 7...d5 { . However, by playing this way we keep enough control over the d5-square. } ) O-O ( { Black can also start with } 7...d6 { and follow up with ...O-O. In both cases, we're going to be playing the same plan of challenging Black's dark-squared bishop. } ) 
8. Be3 d5? { This big mistake is a move that the impatient Black player plays often. Black wants to challenge our central control, but they run into a serious tactical problem. } 
9. O-O-O! } { Suddenly the pawn on d5 is in trouble. } Be6? ( { Black often plays like this because they're worried they will lose the pawn after } 9...d4 10.Nb5! { However, this will cost them much more material! } ) 
10. exd5 Nxd5 
11. Nxd5 Bxd5 
12. c4+- } { The pin costs Black a full piece. } *

