2. This allows us to set ourselves up way more aggressively, and in general at the club level, players are not so good at handling being attacked! } ) { Saving our knight and targeting Black's bishop. This is known as the Potter Variation. } Bb6 { This is the move you will encounter almost always. Black saves their bishop from attack and keeps it on the long g1-a7 diagonal. } 
6. Qe2 { We go for this unusual-looking aggressive setup! There's a few ideas behind this move:

1. Protect the f2-pawn, which can be a little vulnerable given Black's bishop on b6.

2. Cover the e3-square; this is useful since we in some situations will play Bc1-e3 to challenge Black's best piece.

3. Begin clearing pieces from the queenside in order to be able to castle there and get an attacking game with opposite-side castling. }d6 ( { Black has a lot of replies from here. In the Quickstarter, we're going to be looking at the three most popular moves: } 6...d6 { , } ) ( 6...Nge7 { , and } ) ( 6...Nf6 { . } ) { Now we turn our attention to this flexible move, which is considered the main line as it is Black's most popular way of continuing development. Black not only opens up the scope of their light-squared bishop, but they also bring the e5-square under their control. This allows them to bring their knight out to f6 on the next move without having to contend with e4-e5 pushes from White, as we saw in the previous variation. [/variation/28416390/#/7/w] } 
7. Nc3 ( { Developing the knight before the dark-squared bishop is a useful guideline as, most of the time, it's going to be a better move order. For instance, against } 7.Be3 Qf6!? { is an interesting move. } { However, if now Black plays @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/ppp2ppp/1bnp4/8/4P3/1NN5/PPP1QPPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 1 7@@EndFEN@@ 7...Qf6 , we have 8.Nd5 winning Black's bishop straight away. } ) Nf6 ( { The most popular move, which makes sense since the f6-square is the most active square for the knight and Black wants to get ready to castle. Other moves like } 7...Nge7 { or } ) ( 7...Be6 { will transpose to positions covered via different move orders, which is why we are not considering them here. } ) 
8. Be3 { Black's most impactful piece is their bishop on b6, so we seek to challenge it. From here, Black has a wide choice. } O-O { This move is by far the most popular, but it leads to an easy game for us. Perhaps the better plan is to go for an early queenside development and castle queenside. The reason is that now we're going to get a situation with opposite-side castling on the board where we have the much faster attack. } 
9. O-O-O! Re8 } ( { Jumping on the chance to play an attacking position. We will aim to push our kingside pawns in the coming moves. In the Quickstarter, we'll look at Black's two most popular continuations: } 9...Re8 { placing their rook on the semi-open e-file and targeting our e4-pawn, and } ) ( 9...Be6 { completing their minor piece development. } ) { We turn our attention to the most popular continuation. The idea behind this move is simple, Black activates their rook and threatens to take our pawn on e4. } 
10. f3 } } Be6 { Black finishes their minor piece development. } 
11. Kb1 Qe7 } ( { From here, Black has a wide choice. In the full course, we cover all three most popular moves: } 11...Qe7 { , } ) ( 11...Ne5 { and } ) ( 11...Bxe3 { , while here in the Quickstarter, we'll focus on the first of these. } ) 
12. g4! ( { Now that the queen has stepped off of d8, Black is already threatening } 12.-- d5! { so we have to be careful. This kind of move will typically at least equalize for Black since, if you notice, we have more space, but we're actually less developed than Black (all of their minor pieces are out of their starting squares, while we have a bishop still stuck on f1). So, we need to be careful! } ) { White builds up the attack in the usual way! } Nd7 } 
13. h4 ( { Black transfers the knight to d7 from where it cannot be hit with a move like g5. Importantly, Black is now defending their bishop on b6, which means they are free to play } 13.-- a5 { . } { 12...d5? This doesn't work here at all, because of the following: 13.Bxb6 axb6 14.g5!+- The knight has to move, and then we can win a piece with exd5 . } ) { We continue attacking. } a5 { Black follows up with their plan, trying to create some chances on the queenside since we are dominating the centre and kingside. } 
14. a3! { A generally useful move and this position is no exception. We want to stop Black's pawn from reaching all the way to a3 as that would weaken our king. } a4 { Black targets our knight but on the other hand the pawn on a4 may be a weakness in the long run as it can't move or be easily defended. } 
15. Nd4 } { Placing the knight in the centre makes the most sense to me. } Nxd4 
16. Bxd4 Bxd4 
17. Rxd4 $16  } { White stands better here with more space in the centre and kingside, and chances for an attack in the coming moves. Probably we'll play g4-g5 soon, as well as moves like Qe2-f2 and Bf1-e2, to complete our piece development. Black will have to try to stir something up on the queenside, but we have good piece control on that side of the board, and it will be very hard for Black to make a successful pawn break against us.

Overall, I think the main line of the Classical is something that we should be happy to face since the opposite-side castling positions are fun and are objectively a lot better for White.

This brings us to the end of the Quickstarter. I hope that you enjoyed this coverage of the fundamentals of the Scotch, and good luck testing out these lines at the chess board! } *

[Event "Starting Out: The Scotch"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Malaniuk Variation 4...Bb4+ #1"]
[Date "2023.07.18"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C45"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/28718396"]

1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 exd4 { This is the move you will see the majority of the time. It's the clear best move. For an in-depth understanding of why, you can refer to the 'Third Moves for Black' chapter. [/course/179653/2] There, we explain the pros and cons of all of Black's replies that will be covered in this course. } ( { Depending on your level you'll see } 3...exd4 { more or less often. In online games between players rated 0-1400, Black plays it around 60% of the time. While in games between players rated 2000+ we see it played a little over 90% of the time. There's a clear trend here! The higher the rating of your opponent, the more likely that they'll know that } ) ( 3...exd4 { is best and play it automatically. But if you are playing mostly club-level opponents, you can probably expect to play against sidelines about 35-40% of the time. This is one of the great things about playing the Scotch, since for the most part, the sidelines will offer us a great opportunity to get an advantage right off the bat! } ) 
4. Nxd4 { From here, Black has a lot of options. We'll explain these in detail in the 'Fourth Moves for Black' chapter. [/course/179653/6] In the Quickstarter, we'll go over the most popular moves, which at the club level will be in this order: }Bb4+ ( 4...Nxd4?! { A bad idea, allowing us to develop our queen to the powerful d4-square. We're going to face this move a lot, and that's a great thing! } { 4...Bc5 The Classical Variation. One of Black's strong options, developing a piece and hitting our knight on d4. }{ 4...Nf6 The Schmidt - Another solid and popular approach, developing the knight and striking at our e4-pawn. }{ 4...Qf6 An unusual approach, striking at our d4-knight and also putting some pressure against f2. }{ 4...Qh4 The Steinitz variation - similar to the previous line but an even more aggressive post of the queen. This one is actually Black's best scoring line at the club level, so we should be careful! But the good news is White is doing really well here if they know a powerful gambit line that we'll be covering here! }{ 4...Bb4+ The Malaniuk variation. A rare guest at the club level but a popular guest at the master level. The idea behind giving the check is to invite us to play 5.c3 when we will no longer have that square for our knight. The theory can be quite challenging, and I would suggest students rated below 2000 to leave the study of these chapters for the end. }) 
5. c3! } ( { Black gives a check, inviting us to block it with } 5.c3 { , when our knight will no longer have access to the c3-square. } ) { While this line is playable, it's not a black-and-white case that having a pawn on c3 is bad for White. Overall, because we gain time with this move (by forcing Black to move their bishop) I think it's the best way to counter Black's approach. We can either find a different way of developing our knight, or later on play c3-c4 when once again we'll have the option of playing Nb1-c3. } Be7 ( { The most popular alternative to } 5...Bc5 { is to drop the bishop to e7. However, here we have a strong aggressive idea. } ) 
6. Nf5! } { Threatening both the g7-pawn and the bishop on e7. } Bf6 { With this move, Black defends the g7-pawn and stops us from winning the bishop pair. } 
7. Ne3! } { Developing the knight and getting ready to castle. } 
8. f4! } { White was threatening 9.e5 when Black's bishop would be in trouble, so Black stops this. } 
9. Bc4 $16  } -- ( { The bishop finds the most active placement, along the a2-g8 diagonal. Next, we'll play } 9...-- 10.O-O { with a much better middlegame position owing to the extra central space and Black's cramped pieces. We can develop our queen's knight via either a3 or d2 while it's very hard to find a plan for Black here. } )
*

