4. Nxd4 { From here, Black has a lot of options. We'll explain these in detail in the 'Fourth Moves for Black' chapter. [/course/179653/6] In the Quickstarter, we'll go over the most popular moves, which at the club level will be in this order: }Bb4+ ( 4...Nxd4?! { A bad idea, allowing us to develop our queen to the powerful d4-square. We're going to face this move a lot, and that's a great thing! } { 4...Bc5 The Classical Variation. One of Black's strong options, developing a piece and hitting our knight on d4. }{ 4...Nf6 The Schmidt - Another solid and popular approach, developing the knight and striking at our e4-pawn. }{ 4...Qf6 An unusual approach, striking at our d4-knight and also putting some pressure against f2. }{ 4...Qh4 The Steinitz variation - similar to the previous line but an even more aggressive post of the queen. This one is actually Black's best scoring line at the club level, so we should be careful! But the good news is White is doing really well here if they know a powerful gambit line that we'll be covering here! }{ 4...Bb4+ The Malaniuk variation. A rare guest at the club level but a popular guest at the master level. The idea behind giving the check is to invite us to play 5.c3 when we will no longer have that square for our knight. The theory can be quite challenging, and I would suggest students rated below 2000 to leave the study of these chapters for the end. }) 
5. c3! ( { Black gives a check, inviting us to block it with } 5.c3 { , when our knight will no longer have access to the c3-square. } ) { While this line is playable, it's not a black-and-white case that having a pawn on c3 is bad for White. Overall, because we gain time with this move (by forcing Black to move their bishop) I think it's the best way to counter Black's approach. We can either find a different way of developing our knight, or later on play c3-c4 when once again we'll have the option of playing Nb1-c3. } Bc5 { Black usually places their bishop on c5, the most active square available. We've got a very similar position to the Classical Variation, [/variation/28221281/#/4/b] with the only difference being that here Black has coaxed us into putting our pawn on c3 instead of c2. This forces us to change our approach to the opening since we can't go for any plans that involve a quick Nb1-c3. } 
6. Be3 } Bb6 ( { Developing, supporting the knight on d4, and creating the threat of } 6...-- 7.Nxc6 { which would win a piece. } ) ( { Black mostly drops the bishop back, so that it is defended by the pawns and thus stops the threat of 7.Nxc6.

In the course, we'll also cover the dubious alternatives of } 6...Nxd4?! { improving our pawn structure, and } ) ( 6...Qf6?! { seeking to pressure our d4-knight, a plan that is a little ineffective here, given how well-supported it is. } ) 
7. Nf5! { Much like in the 5...Be7 line [/variation/28718396/#/5/b] recently covered, we are once again jumping the knight to f5. The idea is to threaten the g7-pawn and to offer up a bishop exchange when our knight will end up on e3. This is a recurring theme of our play against the Malaniuk, establishing a grip on the d5-square and playing for a space advantage. }g6 ( { From here, Black has two major tries: } 7...Bxe3 { is the classical approach, when we'll get a Maroczy bind (that's a structure when White has pawns on e4 and c4) and the hyper-aggressive } ) ( 7...g6 { . We'll cover these in the Quickstarter, while rarer tries like } ) ( 7...Qf6 { and } ) ( 7...d5!? { are addressed in the main course [/course/179653/19] itself. } ) { This turns out to be a very tricky and theoretically demanding move because of a crazy tactical line that we will have no choice but to go into if Black wishes to take the game there. The upshot is that the position is much better for us, but the downside is that we're going to have to dance with our king! } 
8. Bxb6 } { We begin by capturing on b6 to have the e3-square as a retreat for our knight. } axb6 
9. Ne3 { The knight completes its journey from d4-f5-e3. } Nf6 } { Targeting our e4-pawn. } 
10. f3  itself, but it's a pretty timid move. This move on the other hand has really aggressive intentions, as we will see in Black's next move... } ) 
11. c4 } { White plays this move in order to stop 11...d5 and also to clear up the c3-square for our queen's knight. } d5!? { Black defies the odds and plays ...d5 anyway! This is what we were speaking about when we said that this line can get really crazy, and we don't have any choice but to go into it. The good news, however, is that Black's sacrificial idea is not completely sound against best play. } 
12. cxd5 ( { Capturing with the c-pawn makes sense, since we don't want to play } 12.exd5 { and open up the e-file. } ) Nxe4 } { This is Black's point. They are softening up our centre and opening up the h4-d8 diagonal for their queen. } 
13. fxe4 { We have no choice but to accept the piece sacrifice, but White will stand much better in the end. } Qh4+ 
14. Kd2! { This is the best square since at least here we have stepped off the e-file and we're also not such an easy target for Black's remaining minor pieces as we would be on the e2-square. } Qxe4 
15. Bd3! ( { Black offers up the knight, but in reality, we can't take it because } 15.dxc6 Rd8+ { would cost us our queen. } ) Qd4 } ( { Continuing our development and gaining time against Black's queen. Here it's easy for Black to go wrong. The only testing move is } 15...Qd4 { . } ) 
16. Qb3 $16   of the Malaniuk. } )
