1. e4 { This chapter is informational. All the lines mentioned here are covered in their respective chapters in a lot more detail. The idea of this chapter is to discuss Black's first major decision point (on move 3) and to show why any move other than the main line of 3...exd4 is a little bit dubious. } e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 d6 ( { The starting point of the Scotch. One of the things that appeal about playing the Scotch is that in this position, Black has many possible moves but only one move (3...exd4) is objectively good.

Statistically, the move } 3...exd4 { will be played anywhere from 50-90% of the time against you. That number will be higher or lower depending on the average rating of your opponents. Stronger players know that this is the move to play, so as you become more advanced, you will eventually see this reply almost all the time.

But the good news is that, for most of the students of this course, one of the big benefits of playing the Scotch is that Black will react in different ways, and you will get an advantage as early as Black's third move. Let's now take a look at what the alternatives are, and why they are inferior to } ) ( 3...exd4 { . } ) ( { After } 3...exd4 { , this is the move you will see most often. It's a natural move, seeking to defend the pawn on e5. One of the problems of this move is that it's a little passive as Black locks in their dark-squared bishop. } )
4. Bb5! { There's a few ways to approach this position. The first is 4.d5 , looking to grab as much space in the centre as possible. The second is 4.dxe5 when after 4...dxe5 5.Qxd8+ Black has to play 5...Kxd8 to avoid losing the pawn on e5. While this offers White a small advantage, I believe we can get more with our course recommendation. } exd4 ( { This is going to be our repertoire choice, and we have a full chapter dedicated to this position. The idea is that by pinning Black's knight on c6 we are threatening } 4...-- 5.dxe5 { next, winning the pawn on e5. } ) { Most of the time Black will now take on d4. } 
5. Nxd4 Bd7 { Black addresses the pressure on c6. } 
6. Nc3 $16  } { In this variation, our key idea is going to be to capture on c6 at the right moment and damage Black's pawn structure. Later on, we will use our superiority in the centre to launch an attack on the centre/kingside by pushing our f-pawn to f4. This ensures us a comfortable edge, with White's results in this line being very promising. } *

