1. e4 } e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 Bd6?! ( 3...f6? { Honestly, I don't think there's a need to try to study theory here. This move will usually only be played by very inexperienced opponents since just about any other way of reacting to the threat of capturing the pawn on e5 is better. The important thing to note is that the a2-g8 diagonal is left extremely weakened and so we can just play } 4.Bc4 $16 { next. Also, note that the f6-square is now being occupied, so it will be very difficult for Black to develop their king's knight and bishop to good squares. White is much better and can continue with normal moves such as O-O and Nc3. } ) { Sometimes Black chooses this somewhat awkward way of supporting the e5-pawn. } 
4. c3 exd4?! ( { I like this way of playing. Basically, if Black is not going to play the normal move of } 4...exd4 { , then we can take advantage of this and support the pawn so that if Black ever captures us on d4 then we can recapture with a pawn. } ) { Quite a lot of the time players do end up capturing now, but this very much plays into our strategy. } 
5. cxd4 } { White has built up an ideal centre. } Bb4+ { It may be best for Black to give this check, admitting that d6 was the wrong square for the bishop to begin with. This is because without removing the bishop, it's very difficult for Black to ever complete their development as their d7-pawn is paralyzed. } 
6. Nc3 } { Black has to challenge the centre straight away. Otherwise, we'll steamroll them with a move like 7.d5. } 
7. exd5 Qxd5 { Black uses the fact that our knight is pinned to be able to capture. We are now left with an isolated queen's pawn (IQP) position, but it's a very good version of it for us because of the time that Black has wasted moving their bishop around. } 
8. Be2 Nge7 
9. O-O $16  } { Black will have to move their queen next, and we can follow up with a natural move like 10.a3 asking Black to either move their bishop again or give us the bishop pair and change our structure from an IQP structure to a 'hanging pawns' structure.

We'll leave our analysis here as White's position is very good. My advice if you are interested to improve your play in such positions would be to make a general study of IQP and hanging pawn structures since this type of position is too flexible to lend itself to memorizing lines. } *

