3. d4 d6 { This passive setup is one that we have many ways of responding against and White has been scoring great across all of the variations. The only thing tricky about facing this line is deciding what approach to take! Here are White's possibilities: }
4. Bb5 } } ( 4.d5 { White grabs space and will follow up this move with 5.c4. White gets a good version of the typical King's Indian Defense structure. } ) ( 4.dxe5 { - White sees that after } 4...dxe5 5.Qxd8+ { Black will have to play } 5...Kxd8 { since their knight on c6 has to stay defending the e5-pawn. White hopes to be able to prove an advantage because of Black's misplaced king. } ) ( 4.Bb5 { - White pins the knight and actually takes the game into Ruy Lopez territory. This is because with this move, we transpose to the following line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 d6 4.d4 . Note that it’s also possible to reach the position via a Philidor Defense move order, though that’s more rare.

In this course, we're going to go for the third option. The reason is that the first (4.d5) leads to a closed structure that is, while good, harder to play precisely than other paths. The second option gives a slight edge and leads to simpler play, but with the queens off the board, Black's king does not have so much to worry about on d8, and I feel like our winning chances do go down a little as a result. } ) ( 4.Bb5 { , on the other hand, is a nice mix of easy-to-understand and objective advantage. So, let's dive in to understand why this is so! } ) Bd7?! ( { White simply threatens to play 5.dxe5, winning a pawn. Black now has two major paths they can go down: } 4...exd4 { releasing the tension in the centre or } ) ( 4...Bd7 { using tactics to avoid losing a pawn, as we shall soon see. } { 4...a6? is the third most popular move played by Black, but it is just losing a clean pawn. 5.Bxc6+ bxc6 6.dxe5+- Black is down a pawn and has a worse structure to boot. } ) ( { This move is almost as popular as } 4...exd4 { . It's been played by Grandmasters over the years, usually via the Ruy Lopez move order, but modern computers feel that Black is in some trouble here and tournament results support that as White is scoring great here. } ) 
5. Bxc6 } { Removing the defender of e5. } Bxc6 
