In this course, we're going to go for the third option. The reason is that the first (4.d5) leads to a closed structure that is, while good, harder to play precisely than other paths. The second option gives a slight edge and leads to simpler play, but with the queens off the board, Black's king does not have so much to worry about on d8, and I feel like our winning chances do go down a little as a result. } ) ( 4.Bb5 { , on the other hand, is a nice mix of easy-to-understand and objective advantage. So, let's dive in to understand why this is so! } ) exd4 ( { White simply threatens to play 5.dxe5, winning a pawn. Black now has two major paths they can go down: } 4...exd4 { releasing the tension in the centre or } ) ( 4...Bd7 { using tactics to avoid losing a pawn, as we shall soon see. } { 4...a6? is the third most popular move played by Black, but it is just losing a clean pawn. 5.Bxc6+ bxc6 6.dxe5+- Black is down a pawn and has a worse structure to boot. } ) { Black makes a small concession in the centre by trading off their most central pawn, but now they no longer have to worry about our threat of capturing it. } 
5. Nxd4 } Bd7 } ( { It makes sense for Black to block in this way rather than defend with a move like } 5...Nge7 { since their knight is going to be better placed on the more active f6-square. } ) 
6. Nc3 { You could also castle instead, it will probably just transpose. We are in that stage of the opening where both sides are playing natural moves to finish their development. } Nxd4?! ( { This is a pretty popular alternative to the main reply } 6...Nf6 { , which we'll examine next, but it's something we should welcome as now our queen is going to establish herself on the strong d4-square. } ) 
7. Bxd7+ { Taking first is slightly better than letting them take us, since if we do that our knight ends up on the odd-looking b5-square. } Qxd7 
8. Qxd4 Nf6 
9. Bg5 { Developing with tempo makes sense here, though many good moves exist for White. } Be7 
10. O-O-O $16  } { We arrive at our desired setup. From here, we can consider putting a pawn on f3 to support the advance of our g-pawn to launch an attack. We can also play with ideas of 11.e5 if Black is not careful. At some point, we should also take some time out to improve our king safety by placing it on b1 to avoid tactical shots from Black.

Overall, we can say that we're in a pretty typical but very good position where we have well-placed pieces, central control, and the possibility of an attack on the kingside. Black, on the other hand, is not having so much fun! } *


