1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 d6 { This passive setup is one that we have many ways of responding against and White has been scoring great across all of the variations. The only thing tricky about facing this line is deciding what approach to take! Here are White's possibilities: }
4. Bb5 } ( 4.d5 { White grabs space and will follow up this move with 5.c4. White gets a good version of the typical King's Indian Defense structure. } ) ( 4.dxe5 { - White sees that after } 4...dxe5 5.Qxd8+ { Black will have to play } 5...Kxd8 { since their knight on c6 has to stay defending the e5-pawn. White hopes to be able to prove an advantage because of Black's misplaced king. } ) ( 4.Bb5 { - White pins the knight and actually takes the game into Ruy Lopez territory. This is because with this move, we transpose to the following line: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 d6 4.d4 . Note that it’s also possible to reach the position via a Philidor Defense move order, though that’s more rare.

In this course, we're going to go for the third option. The reason is that the first (4.d5) leads to a closed structure that is, while good, harder to play precisely than other paths. The second option gives a slight edge and leads to simpler play, but with the queens off the board, Black's king does not have so much to worry about on d8, and I feel like our winning chances do go down a little as a result. } ) ( 4.Bb5 { , on the other hand, is a nice mix of easy-to-understand and objective advantage. So, let's dive in to understand why this is so! } ) exd4 ( { White simply threatens to play 5.dxe5, winning a pawn. Black now has two major paths they can go down: } 4...exd4 { releasing the tension in the centre or } ) ( 4...Bd7 { using tactics to avoid losing a pawn, as we shall soon see. } { 4...a6? is the third most popular move played by Black, but it is just losing a clean pawn. 5.Bxc6+ bxc6 6.dxe5+- Black is down a pawn and has a worse structure to boot. } ) { Black makes a small concession in the centre by trading off their most central pawn, but now they no longer have to worry about our threat of capturing it. } 
5. Nxd4 Bd7 } ( { It makes sense for Black to block in this way rather than defend with a move like } 5...Nge7 { since their knight is going to be better placed on the more active f6-square. } ) 
6. Nc3 { You could also castle instead, it will probably just transpose. We are in that stage of the opening where both sides are playing natural moves to finish their development. } Nf6 
7. O-O } Be7 
8. Nxc6! ( { With this natural developing move, Black suddenly creates an unexpected threat. And that is to play 8...Nxd4! and start exchanging pieces in good fashion. We should anticipate this plan, but let's also show what happens if we just play a very quiet move. } 8.Re1?! { This line is here only to show what will happen if we let Black carry out their plan. } 8...Nxd4! 9.Bxd7+ Nxd7! { Black takes with the knight! This is something they could never have done before putting their bishop on e7. Why is this? } 10.Qxd4 { Well, if you imagine this position but with Black's bishop on f8, the problem would be that they would not find it so easy to finish their development since we're putting pressure on g7. This is the reason why I mentioned after 7...Be7 that with this natural developing move, Black suddenly has a strategic threat. } 10...O-O { By the way, if you do allow this plan in the future, there is no need to panic. White is not worse here, in fact, we should still be slightly better because of our greater central control. It's just that Black has managed to obtain a better piece setup than we should have let them get.

Black can transfer their knight to c5 and/or place their bishop on f6. This allows them to pressure our queen as well as our pawn on e4. The reason why we are taking some time to understand this is so that we better understand why we are meeting 7...Be7 with a very specific plan. } ) { The moment has come to capture because otherwise, Black will take us on d4 and, as we have just seen, obtain a much better setup. Quiet moves won't do in this position! } Bxc6 ( { Black offers up an exchange of bishops. Honestly, neither option is much stronger than the other, so we should treat them similarly. Here the game does end up with one set of minor pieces less, so it's more likely that you'll get a simplified middlegame or an endgame than with } 8...bxc6 { . But that's not a problem for us since we have the better pawn structure, and that will benefit us across all endgames. } ) 
9. Bxc6+ { We should capture here to damage Black's structure. } bxc6 
10. b3 } { This is a nice plan, and one that we will generally go for in these structures. The idea is two-fold. Firstly, we anticipate that Black will castle kingside when our bishop from b2 generates some nice attacking possibilities. Secondly, after 9...bxc6 Black has a semi-open b-file where they could place a rook. So by setting ourselves up in this way, we take the sting out of any activity they could get on the queenside. } O-O 
11. Bb2 d5? ( { This is a really nice and comfortable position for us to play because what happens in practice is that Black really struggles to come up with a plan, and often that leads to them becoming impatient and making big mistakes which we can take advantage of. Here Black has tried a lot of moves, but by far the most common have been the impatient } 11...d5? { , the rerouting move } ) ( 11...Nd7!? { and the flexible } ) ( 11...Re8 { . } ) { This impatient move plays into our hands, since now the pawn on d5 is a really easy target. } 
12. Qf3 } { Defending on e4 and preparing Rad1 next to put more pressure on the pawn. } Qd7 
13. Rad1 Rad8 { Black is hanging onto the pawn by a thread. } 
14. Rfe1 $16  } -- ( { White is much better here. We have a couple of different possibilities. One is to play 15.e5 grabbing space and going for an attack along the central files. Another option is to play } 14...-- 15.exd5 cxd5 16.Nxd5! Nxd5 17.c4 { when we'll get our piece back with Black's structure being super weak. Your choice will largely depend on your preferred style, but in either case Black is in trouble. } )
