9. Bd3 } } { Supporting the e4-pawn. The bishop may come alive in the future if we can play f2-f4 and e4-e5. } O-O 
10. f4! } { As usual, we expand in the centre. From here on out we have ideas based around pushing our pawn to e5 which can not only damage Black's structure but open up a lot of lines of attack against Black's king. } Rb8 
11. h3 } { White takes time to control the important g4-square. } Re8 { Black activates the second rook. } 
12. b3! } { In this structure we'll often fianchetto our bishop, as not only is it very effectively placed on the long diagonal, but it also shuts down the activity of Black's rook on b8. } Bf8 
13. Bb2 } { A lot of the time, Black will play this move in order to get the c6-square for their bishop. Their intention is to put a lot of pressure on our e4-pawn. However, Black has to be very careful. Here White already has a crushing sequence! Note: if Black plays something else, we can just slowly build up our position with the typical moves of 14.Qf3 and 15.Rae1 while waiting for the best opportunity to blow open the position with an e4-e5 push. } 
14. e5! dxe5 
15. fxe5 Rxe5 { Black has won a pawn for now, but all of White's pieces are suddenly extremely active, so it's no surprise that we have a winning tactic. } 
16. Ne4! } Re6 ( { Black tries to hold the position, but it still falls apart. } 16...Rxe4? 17.Bxf6+- { Next we will take on e4 and emerge up an exchange and with a much better pawn structure. } ) 
17. Nxf6+ gxf6 
