1) The system with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@ 3...d6 is the second most popular move after 3...exd4, and so you will see it quite often.

2) In general, we should be very happy to see it, as there are many ways to play in order to put Black under pressure.

3) 4.d5 is appealing for players who like to play closed positions with a space advantage. 4.dxe5 is okay if you want to minimize risk. Our recommended move of 4.Bb5 takes the game into what is a good line of the Ruy Lopez for White. It leads to an open game that suits our Scotch tastes, while at the same time allowing us to set up in a simple attacking fashion.

4) The main move we will see after 4.Bb5 is 4...exd4 . After 5.Nxd4 , we will have a lot of pressure against Black’s pinned knight on c6. Eventually we will capture on c6 and double Black’s pawns.

5) This will lead to a position where White has a central space advantage, while Black might hope to get some pressure going with their rooks along the semi-open b-file and also against our e4-pawn by placing their king’s rook on e8.

6) Keeping this in mind, our best setup is to play b2-b3, fianchetto our dark-squared bishop, and push the f-pawn to f4.

7) Other useful moves to keep in mind are h2-h3 to control the important g4-square, as well as Qd1-f3 to keep the e4-pawn well-protected.

8) A lot of the time, the plan will be to push your e-pawn to e5 at the right moment. Be careful not to play this too soon, after all, Black doesn’t have any clear plan, so we shouldn’t rush.

In closing, the entire system is quite bad for Black, and I believe that as long as we have a good idea of what we covered in this chapter, we’ll be able to look forward to facing this system and can expect to score very well and get fun, attacking games. } *

