{ This chapter is informational in nature, and you don't have to commit anything to memory here since all the lines discussed are covered in much more detail in their respective chapters. The purpose of this chapter is to provide you with an introduction to the different systems that we'll be facing as Scotch players after Black's fourth move. } 1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 exd4 
4. Nxd4 } { We reach the first 'serious' juncture of the Scotch. What is meant by the word 'serious' is that while Black had a wide choice on move 3, none of the moves besides 3...exd4 were very appealing. Here however, it's a different story. Black has several strong systems to choose from. In this chapter, we'll show a quick overview of the serious systems that Black can go for. These are: }Nf6 ( 4...Bc5 { (The Classical Variation) } { 4...Nf6 (The Schmidt Variation) } { 4...Qh4 (The Steinitz) } { 4...Qf6 (I don't think this has a name, but it's stronger than the Steinitz!) } { 4...Nxd4? (The early exchange, super popular at the club level but not very good) } { 4...Bb4+ (The Malaniuk Variation)

In the course itself, we'll also take a brief look at some rarer sidelines like 4...Ne5 , 4...Nge7 and 4...d6 . Okay, let's dive in! } { 4...Nxd4? Exchanging knights is not a good idea. We already covered [/variation/28221190/#/4/b] this in the 'Third Moves for Black - A fork in the road' overview chapter, so we won't speak about this again. But it's a move you should be happy to face, and the good news is that it's the most popular move at the club level. } ) 
5. Nxc6 ( { The Schmidt Variation is as solid as it comes. Black invites us to damage their pawn structure by playing } 5.Nxc6 { , but their claim is that after } 5...bxc6 { , they will get enough counterplay in the form of a strong central pawn mass and fast development. And, to be honest, they have a point. In my view, this is the toughest system to prove an advantage against. } ) { We'll be grabbing the bull by the horns and damaging Black's structure since I don't think there's anything better to go for. } bxc6 
6. Nc3 ( { Historically, White has played } 6.e5 { ,the so-called Mieses Variation, the most, kicking the knight around. It's not a bad line, but Black has shown over time that they can equalize so long as they know what they're doing. And the problem is that the lines become ultra-sharp, and it's easy to lose the thread as White unless you spend a lot of time studying the subtleties of these positions. That's why we're taking a more conservative approach, just defending the pawn on e4 for now. } ) Bb4  like } 6...d5 { or } ) ( 6...Bc5 { . } ) 
7. Bd3 { Defending the pawn on e4 since Black was threatening 7...Nxe4. We're not worried about Black taking our knight on c3 since even though our pawn structure would get damaged, we would win the bishop pair, and that is a more important factor. This is also discussed in more detail [/variation/28221331/#/7/w] within those chapters. } d5 { Black challenges us in the centre. } 
8. exd5 cxd5 
9. O-O O-O 
10. h3 $14  } ( { The most popular move is } 10.Bg5 { , but over the years, Black has neutralized the effect of this pin. Our move is a more modern treatment of this line, with the idea being to control the g4-square before placing our queen on f3 next. } )-- ( { Black will often play 10...h6 here taking away Bc1-g5 ideas for good, but that's okay because our plan is to place the bishop on f4. We'll dive into this position in more depth and show a bunch of typical manoeuvres and ideas. Our main strategic idea here is to try to take advantage of Black's loose pawn structure on the centre and queenside.

Meanwhile, Black will try to prove that their solid central control and the ability to place their pieces on active squares offset their slightly damaged structure. Objectively, that's true. According to today's strongest computers, the position is approximately equal. Still, White's position is, at the very least, easier to play for humans, and the results bear this out. Over 20,000 online blitz & rapid games, White has scored 50% wins versus Black's 39% wins. Hopefully, by the time we cover this material in depth, you'll be able to score even higher than these averages!

One closing remark: this line is more positional in nature than most of the rest of the course. But hopefully, this isn't something to be seen as a bad thing, since it gives us an opportunity to focus on outplaying our opponents based on things like pawn structures and transitioning to better endgames. } )
