5. Qxd4 } ( { Additionally, as we see in many chapters, White is often happy to castle queenside. After } 5.Qxd4 { , we will be one move closer to doing this if we wish to. } ) d6 } ( { From here, Black has tried many things. We can't cover everything, so we'll tackle the five most popular continuations, which are } 5...d6 { , } ) ( 5...Nf6 { , } ) ( 5...c5 { , } ) ( 5...Qf6 { and } ) ( 5...b6 { . } ) { The most popular move. Black covers the e5-square with their pawn so that they can play 6...Nf6 next without having to worry about us playing 7.e5. The downside to this way of playing is that Black's setup is very passive. Not only have they brought our queen out to the very strong d4-square, but they have given up on trying to find an active placement for their dark-squared bishop. } 
6. Nc3 } { We could play in a lot of ways, but developing the queen's knight is flexible, and the possibility of jumping into d5 or b5 early on is useful in some lines. } Nf6 
7. Bf4 } { I believe this is the best square for the bishop, because from here we make a potential e4-e5 push in the future as strong as possible. } Be7 ( { Black continues their development and will usually castle on the next move. This is the move you will see almost always. Sometimes Black plays } 7...Be6 { first and then goes 8...Be7, but it doesn't matter to us in which order they place their bishops on e7 and e6 since we'll end up getting the same position either way. } ) 
8. O-O-O O-O { In fact, this is the only reasonable move from Black, as we could see in the line after 8...Be6?! [/variation/28221246/#/8/b] that White already had concrete threats. So Black should definitely hurry to bring their king to safety.

From here, White has a few reasonable ways to continue. The conventional approach would be to play a plan with moves such as 9.f3, 10.Kb1, 11.g4, 12.h4 and launch a kingside attack. If you feel comfortable with those positions, I would recommend that you simply play that and forget about the theory that we will now show. However, this plan of attack is one seen in other chapters of the course, so here I want to show another promising and more direct way that you can force a better middlegame. } 
