10. exd6 Bf6!? { This is the tricky line, and in practice Black has scored pretty well here as the White side gets a little confused by the messy nature of the position with so many points under attack. } 
11. Qd2 } Bxc3 ( 11...cxd6?! 12.f3 { I like kicking away the knight. } 12...Ne5 13.Ne4+- { White will play either 14.Qxd6 or 14.Nxd6 next, a clean pawn to the good. } ) 
12. bxc3! } cxd6 ( { We have to capture with the pawn since our queen is protecting against } 12...Nxf2 { . } ) 
13. Bxd6 Re8 
14. Bc4 $16  } { This is the final position. The important thing I want to comment is that although our pawn structure may look a little ugly, we're going to play 15.Bb3 next, and our strong control of the dark squares means that we're actually pretty safe. And in the end, the bishop pair + our extra pawn is what really marks the difference, so the position is much much better for White. } *

