1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 exd4 
4. Nxd4 Ne5? ( { In this chapter, we'll be focusing on two rare knight moves: } 4...Ne5?! { and } ) ( 4...Nge7 { . Neither is particularly scary. The first of these is dubious since Black moves their only developed piece for a second time. The second is more reasonable, but still, the knight is generally better placed on f6 than on the more passive e7 square. } { The other move that is acknowledged in this chapter is 4...d6 , though it's only done to briefly mention that this move transposes to the 3...d6 - Transposition to the Ruy Lopez chapter. [/course/179653/4] The good news is that this has no independent value, as with our next move, we'll go back to a position covered via the 3...d6 move order. 5.Bb5 and we have transposed here. [/variation/28221211/#/5/w] } ) { This is a pretty dramatic way for Black to avoid the possibility of exchanging knights, but it's a bad move. The guideline that you shouldn't move the same piece too many times in the opening definitely applies here! In the near future, we may also push our pawn to f4 and win even more time against Black's jumping knight. } 
5. Nc3 } { We can begin with a simple developing move. } Bc5 } ( { Black develops and pressures our knight on d4 and indirectly targets our pawn on f2. } 5...Nf6? { From here, the knight will be extremely vulnerable. } 6.f4 Ng6 7.e5+- { The knight has no other square than back to its starting point on g8. Black has gifted us several tempi (moves), and so we're already completely winning. We can even castle queenside over the coming moves and keep running our pawns up the board on the centre and kingside. } ) 
6. Bf4 ( { Against 5...Bc5 I prefer to play in this way just to avoid weakening the g1-a7 diagonal, but you could also play } 6.f4 { if you wanted to be more aggressive. But this plan is simple and strong. } ) d6 { Black defends their knight. } 
7. Qd2 { Setting up the queen-bishop battery. } Nf6 
8. O-O-O $16  O-O? ( { White has a big advantage and we can continue with moves like 9.f3, 10.Kb1 and then push our g-pawn to get a very strong attack. An added bonus of this position is that most of the time, Black goes wrong with } 8...O-O { so let's quickly take a look at how we can punish this mistake. } ) 
9. Nb3! } { Out of the blue we have two threats! Both of them work off the same principle that the d6-pawn cannot move without Black's queen being lost. } Ned7 { Black has to play an ugly-looking move like this one to avoid losing a piece. However, now we have many strong ways to continue. } 
10. Nxc5 { First, we win Black's strong bishop. } Nxc5 
11. e5+- } { And then we use the fact that the d6-pawn is still pinned to break through in the centre, blasting open the position when our development is much better than Black's. The combination of our better-placed pieces and the bishop pair will overwhelm Black in the centre. White is winning. } *

