1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 exd4 
4. Nxd4 Nge7  } ) { Black's idea with this move is that at some point, they wish to trade off their c6-knight for our d4-knight, and then place their other knight on c6, hitting our queen. At first glance, it seems logical, but there are some problems for Black in playing this way, which we'll now dive into. } 
5. Nc3 } { We begin, as is often the case, by developing our queen's knight and waiting for Black to play their hand. } g6? { At the club level, this is actually the most common continuation, but it is (somewhat incredibly!) a losing mistake. The point is that Black's dark squares are left far too weak and we have one crushing move here. } 
6. Bg5! } { Black develops and is hoping to gain a little time by forcing us to respond to their threat of capturing our d4-knight. } 
7. Nd5! } O-O ( { A beautiful move, ignoring the attack on our d4-knight and ganging up on the pinned e7-knight instead. Our threat is simply to play } 7...-- 8.Nxc6 { next, after which we'll win the e7-knight for free. Black is already completely lost. Let's explore some possible moves: } ) { This move doesn't just lose a piece - it will end up with White winning Black's queen! } 
8. Nxc6 bxc6 
9. Nxe7+ Kh8 
10. Nxg6+ } { We will capture Black's queen on the next move. } *

