9. Nb5 } Kd8 { Black has to save the pawn, but now that Black has lost castling rights we have no fear of playing down a pawn. } 
10. Re1 } ( { Other moves are also really good for White, such as } 10.Rb1 { or } ) ( 10.Bd3 { , but our move is a very natural choice as we immediately make Black's queen feel uncomfortable on e4. } ) d6? { It's a testament to how problematic Black's position is that this losing move has been the second most popular continuation in classical games! } 
11. Nxd6! { The sacrifice works as there are too many open lines of attack and our domination of the dark squares is impossible for Black to deal with. } cxd6 
12. Qxd6+ Bd7 { Black can also try to block the check in this way, and here it's important to be precise with our next move. } 
13. Bf4! } { Threatening an invasion on } { c7 against some of Black's possible defensive replies like { 13...Qe6 or 13...Qd5 . } Rc8 { Black covers the weakness on c7 but this gives us time to continue to build the attack. } 
14. Rad1 } { Threatening checkmate on d7. } Qe6 
15. Qd2+- } { Keeping the queens on the board. You may wish to analyse this position further, but Black is completely lost here because they are paralysed in the centre, and the bishop on d7 cannot be further defended. Soon we'll move our light-squared bishop with a powerful discovery attack on the Black queen. } *

