3. d4 exd4 
4. Nxd4 Qh4?! } { This is known as the Steinitz Variation. Black immediately targets our pawn and, at the same time, pressures the f2-point. This means that if Black follows up with ...Bc5, we have to be careful to avoid getting checkmated early!

That said, this move is not especially good because Black's queen steps out prematurely. Importantly, the queen no longer protects the c7-pawn from h4, and, since we have a knight on d4, we can, at the right moment, try to play Nd4-Nb5 and cause Black some problems. } 
5. Nc3 Bb4 } ( { For now, we continue our development and protect the e4-pawn. From here, the move we will most commonly see is } 5...Bb4 { . This is in fact the only good move. The next most common tries are } ) ( 5...Bc5 { and } ) ( 5...Nf6 { , but both of these moves allow us to build a big advantage straight out of the opening. Let's see how. } ) { This is the only good move for Black and the logical follow-up to 4...Qh4. This is because, with our knight pinned, Black is now threatening to play ...Qxe4+. This moment is the most important of the entire chapter, since, in order to get an advantage, we must remember to play one move and one move only. Everything else gives Black a good game or even an advantage. } 
6. Be2! { A great move! White recognises that it's more trouble than it's worth to try to hang onto the pawn on e4, but that Black's primitive approach to the opening has left them at risk of falling too far behind in development. So, we allow Black to 'achieve their goal' and win the pawn, but in exchange, we're going to have a huge initiative. The good news is that the computers are on our side. White is going to have much more than just compensation for the pawn. Let's take a look. } ( 6.Qd3?! { Here is a sample line as to why it's best to avoid trying to hang onto the pawn. } 6...Nf6 { Black renews the threat against the pawn. } 7.Nxc6?! { Many White players have tried to exchange here, spotting that once the c6-knight is off the board for Black, we can push the pawn to e5 to try to save it. The problem is that we are accelerating Black's development in this way. } 7...dxc6 8.e5 { Our pawn will not be safe on e5. } 8...Ng4 $17 { Suddenly, Black has huge pressure against much of our position, and White is already battling to try to avoid a quick defeat. } ) Bxc3+ ( { Sometimes Black exchanges here before capturing on e4, but it's inferior to } 6...Qxe4 { . } ) 
7. bxc3 Qxe4 
