9. cxd4 } Ne7 { Black tries to keep the e-file closed as much as possible. } 
10. Re1 } Qh4 ( { But unfortunately for them, we are in time! This is the most precise move for a subtle reason that can be seen if Black castles now: } 10...O-O? { runs into } 11.Bg4!+- { winning a piece. Note: going to the g4 square is important as we cut off the possibility of Black playing ...Qh4 from where the queen would be defending the knight on e7. } { This is why we play 10.Re1! rather than something like 10.Bf3? first. } ) { The most stubborn defense. Black anticipates our Bg4 idea and keeps contact with the knight on e7 before preparing to castle on the next move. } 
11. g3 Qf6 } { Black stays protecting the knight; the goal for them is to be able to castle. } 
12. h4 $16  } -- ( { White is relentless. Now if Black plays } 12...O-O { we can play } 13.Bg5 { with further pressure. Since this is not designed to be an advanced repertoire, we won't get into more detail than this as it's very unlikely you'll reach this position (and much more likely that Black goes wrong earlier and gives you chances to win straight out of the opening). } { Here if you wish to study this position further, I will recommend checking out 12...h6 and 12...0-0 with the help of an engine and see how to keep squeezing Black. Objectively White is close to winning, but admittedly you will need to be quite precise and perhaps spend 10-20 minutes studying this position with a computer if you want to understand it well. } )
