Keep in mind that due to the highly dynamic and flexible character of the position, there are many possible variations containing lots of branches. This means that we will just show some illustrative continuations as it would be impossible to do a full analysis of the position, even if this course was intended for advanced students. If you wish to understand the position in more depth, here are a few things you can do:

1) Analyse from here with a computer. Ask yourself what moves look good to you, then cross-check your intuition with the computer's evaluation. Input the ideas you had and let the computer show you the good and bad parts of your thought process.

2) If you have one, play this position (with both colours) against a chess buddy/training partner. That way, you get a better feel for both sides of the coin. A bonus of this method is that you and your partner can start from the starting position, so it helps both of you to memorize the variations. } ) { Evicting the knight is far and away the most popular line chosen by Black, which makes sense as the knight is a very bothersome piece to our opponents. } 
10. Nd4 } Nxd4 { Black usually captures on d4, probably because of a mix of factors. Two that come to mind are:

a) being worried that with the knights on the board, the pressure against Black's queenside is really significant

b) now the d-file will be closed, making Black's king a little safer on d8. } 
11. cxd4 { The benefit for us is that now our queenside pawn structure is no longer a cause for concern, and in fact, we have a really good grip on the centre. } Nf6 { Black goes about trying to complete their development. } 
12. Re1 Re8 ( { The position starts to look very similar to the variation analysed after 9...Nf6. [/variation/28221264/#/9/b] And in fact, after Black's most popular reply of } 12...Re8 { if we follow up with } 13.Bg5 { , we reach the exact same very promising position as we did in that line. } ) 
13. Bg5 $16  { White is much better here with a lot of pressure across the board. Black has to be extremely careful to avoid a quick loss and faces an uphill battle trying to finish their development while keeping their king alive.

Learning Point of this Chapter:

1) @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4...Qh4?! is not an objectively good idea. It’s overly ambitious, and as long as we play accurately and are willing to sacrifice a pawn against best play, we can get a really strong attack for a very small material investment.

2) After 5.Nc3 Black has many different ways to go wrong, such as 5...Bc5? or 5...Nf6? } { 3) Black’s best move by far is @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/3NP2q/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 2 5@@EndFEN@@ 5...Bb4 . Here we need to be prepared to sacrifice a pawn with 6.Be2! In exchange, we’ll get a very big initiative and long-term attacking chances.

4) @@StartFEN@@r1b1k1nr/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/1b1Nq3/2N5/PPP1BPPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@ 7.Ndb5! targeting the undefended pawn on c7 is an important point to keep in mind, highlighting the drawback of Black moving their queen away from its starting square on d8.

5) Black’s best move is 7...Bxc3+ when we should be prepared to double our pawn structure with 8.bxc3! This is done so that we can keep the pressure on the c7-pawn.

6) The middlegame is tactically very rich, and advanced students are encouraged to study it further if they wish. That said, objectively speaking, we have a big advantage, so most students will earn good results by relying on other skills like calculation and pattern recognition in the middlegame, without having to worry about knowing much more theory. } *

