1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 exd4 
4. Nxd4 Bc5 ( { This is the Classical Variation and has withstood the test of time. Alongside } 4...Nf6 { , these two moves represent the gold standard for how Black deals with the Scotch and will be where the majority of your tough theoretical battles take place. White can respond to this move in a variety of ways, namely three main ways. } )
5. Nb3 } { The first is to play 5.Be3 supporting the knight. The second is to play 5.Nxc6 seeking to cause some damage to Black's structure.

The last is our choice for this repertoire to drop the knight back to b3 and target Black's dark-squared bishop. There are two reasons why we're choosing this approach:

1. The theory is less developed here, so there's less for us to study and more likely that our opponents will not respond correctly.

2. This allows us to set ourselves up way more aggressively, and in general, at the club level, players are not so good at handling being attacked! } { Saving our knight and targeting Black's bishop. This is known as the Potter Variation. } Bb4+ 
6. c3! } { Again, Black has the plan of a fast ...d5 push. This move would steal our one key advantage of extra space, so we must watch out for this. } 
7. g3 { This is the simplest way of beefing up our control of the d5-square. } Nf6 
8. Bg2 O-O 
9. O-O d6  That said, there we have the knight on c3 while here we have a pawn. So we can't do the plan we do there of planting a knight on d5. } 
10. h3 } { Controlling the g4-square is useful in these structures. The reason is that we often want either our bishop on e3 or to push our f-pawn to f4. In either case, controlling the g4-square to stop all ideas with ...Ng4 or ...Bg4 is useful. You often see this move played by the White side when they go for a Fianchetto system of the King's Indian Defense, for instance. } Be6 } { Black wants to break with ...d5, but here we can use the fact that our pawn is on c3 to our advantage with our next move. } 
11. Nd4! } { Centralizing our knight and at the same time targeting Black's light-squared bishop. } Nxd4 ( { Black shouldn't try to play } 11...d5? { since after } 12.Nxe6 { the bishop pair is really strong while Black has to play } 12...fxe6 { which will loosen their pawn structure. This is why their best move is to get rid of our strong knight. } ) 
12. cxd4! } -- ( { White ends up with a really good structure. We'll likely develop the knight to c3 next while the move } 12...d5 { can be met by } 13.e5! { when we'll have a really strong 4 vs 3 pawn majority on the kingside. Besides this, we're also going to be looking to play f2-f4 in the coming moves. } )
