1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 exd4 
4. Nxd4 Bc5 ( { This is the Classical Variation and has withstood the test of time. Alongside } 4...Nf6 { , these two moves represent the gold standard for how Black deals with the Scotch and will be where the majority of your tough theoretical battles take place. White can respond to this move in a variety of ways, namely three main ways. } )
5. Nb3 { The first is to play 5.Be3 supporting the knight. The second is to play 5.Nxc6 seeking to cause some damage to Black's structure.

The last is our choice for this repertoire, to drop the knight back to b3 and target Black's dark-squared bishop. There are two reasons why we're choosing this approach:

1. The theory is less developed here, so there's less for us to study and more likely that our opponents will not respond correctly.

2. This allows us to set ourselves up way more aggressively, and in general, at the club level, players are not so good at handling being attacked! } { Saving our knight and targeting Black's bishop. This is known as the Potter Variation. } Bxf2+? { This unsound piece sacrifice is the second most popular choice at the beginner level. We should be very happy to see it, as Black has no significant compensation for the piece. } 
6. Kxf2 } Qh4+ 
7. g3 Qxe4 
8. Qe2+- ( { Swapping queens is probably the easiest path, but you can also continue with } 8.Bg2 { gaining more time against Black's queen as our king is perfectly safe. In either case, White is completely winning. } ) *

