1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 exd4 
4. Nxd4 Bc5 ( { This is the Classical Variation and has withstood the test of time. Alongside } 4...Nf6 { , these two moves represent the gold standard for how Black deals with the Scotch and will be where the majority of your tough theoretical battles take place. White can respond to this move in a variety of ways, namely three main ways. } )
5. Nb3 { The first is to play 5.Be3 supporting the knight. The second is to play 5.Nxc6 seeking to cause some damage to Black's structure.

The last is our choice for this repertoire, to drop the knight back to b3 and target Black's dark-squared bishop. There are two reasons why we're choosing this approach:

1. The theory is less developed here, so there's less for us to study and more likely that our opponents will not respond correctly.

2. This allows us to set ourselves up way more aggressively, and in general, at the club level, players are not so good at handling being attacked! } { Saving our knight and targeting Black's bishop. This is known as the Potter Variation. } Be7 ( { Besides the main line of } 5...Bb6 { , this is the other logical square that Black can place their bishop on. They are arguing that having provoked our knight to move to the b3-square is advantageous to them as our knight was more central on d4. While on b3 it may not be central, it is more stable, and Black has had to spend a bunch of time moving their bishop around so it's a double-edged sword and we shouldn't be unhappy here. } ) 
6. Nc3 } d6?! ( { This is less precise than } 6...Nf6 { because here Black already lets us know that they don't plan on breaking with a fast ...d5 push. And so we don't need to go for a fianchettoed approach. } ) 
