1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 exd4 
4. Nxd4 Bc5 
5. Nb3 Bb6 { Dropping the bishop back to b6 is not only the best move but by far the most popular. After all, one of the key ideas for Black when playing the Classical variation (4...Bc5) is to get their dark-squared bishop on the strong g1-a7 diagonal. } 
6. Qe2 } ( { This is the start of our aggressive approach! There's a few ideas behind this move:

1. Protect the f2-pawn, which can be a little vulnerable given Black's bishop on b6.

2. Cover the e3-square, which allows us to often play Bc1-e3 challenging Black's best piece.

3. Begin clearing queenside pieces, in order to be able to go for an opposite side castling position.

By the way, most of the time, it doesn't matter whether White begins with } 6.Qe2 { , as we are recommending, or the more popular } ) ( 6.Nc3 { . The reason why we're choosing } ) ( 6.Qe2 { is seen in the following line: } ) ( 6.Qe2 Qf6 7.a4! Nd4 8.Nxd4 Bxd4 9.c3! { As you can see, in this rare line, we end up going for the move } { 9.c3! , which would be impossible if we had already planted our knight there on move 6. So, it's a subtle point, but in case you were curious, there you have it! } )Qe7? { Turning back to this position, we can say that Black has quite a lot of approaches they can take here. In this first chapter on the Classical, we'll cover the early pawn push 6...a5 , as well as Black's two reasonable queen moves 6...Qf6 and 6...Qe7 . In the next chapter, [/course/179653/13] we'll talk about Black's second and third most popular replies, the two knight moves of 6...Nf6 and 6...Nge7 . In the third and final chapter, [/course/179653/14] we'll focus on the main line: 6...d6 . } { This move doesn't make much sense, as the queen on e7 is very vulnerable to a quick knight jump to d5. } 
7. Nc3 Nf6 { Unsurprisingly, most of the time Black has developed their knight to f6 in order to protect the d5-square. But this has a big problem. } 
8. Bg5! } h6? ( { Now the knight is pinned and we are threatening } 8...-- 9.Nd5 { . } ) ( { Most Black players go horribly wrong here and try to kick our annoying bishop away immediately. } 8...Qe6 { Black can avoid losing directly with a move like this, but after } 9.O-O-O $16 { , we get a normal-looking position but much better than most since Black has wasted two moves to place their queen on the awkward e6-square. } ) 
9. Nd5! } { Black's pawn structure is about to be ruined. } Qe5 
10. Bxf6 gxf6 
11. O-O-O+- } { White is completely winning as not only is Black's development terrible, but they have no good place to shelter their king as White's attack with a move like 12.f4 will be too fast for them to be able to bring their king to the queenside. } *

