8. Be3 } { Black's most impactful piece is their bishop on b6, so we seek to challenge it. From here, Black has a wide choice. } O-O { This move is by far the most popular, and one of the many good reasons for playing this system as White. That's because in my view the best approach from Black is to avoid an opposite side castling position and instead play for queenside castling. The reason is that our attack is simply a lot faster than Black's! } 
9. O-O-O! { Jumping on the chance to play an attacking position. We will aim to push our kingside pawns in the coming moves and argue that Black's attack is much weaker than ours. The only tricky part is that here Black has lots of moves that they can play. At the club level, they go like this (from most popular to least popular): }Re8 } ( 9...Re8 { Black places their rook on the semi-open e-file and targets our e4-pawn immediately. } { 9...Be6 Black completes their minor piece development. } { 9...Qe7 Stepping the queen off the d-file. This move will transpose to the same positions reached via 9...Be6 . } { 9...Bxe3+ A bad move as our queen stands better on e3, but many players have a habit of exchanging pieces whenever possible so you'll see it quite often. 9...a5 Black tries to launch their own attack, but here it's a big mistake. } ) { Now that we've looked at all of Black's other popular options, we turn our attention to the most popular continuation. The idea behind this move is simple, Black activates their rook and threatens to take our pawn on e4. } 
