11. Kb1 ( { I really like to start with this prophylactic king move and not the typical pawn advance of } 11.g4 { , since if we play like this, then after } 11...Ne5 { , Black is threatening both } 12.-- Nexg4 { and } { 12...Bc4 , which can lead to some complications we would rather avoid. In this way, we first focus on improving our king's safety, and make a decision on exactly what to do next depending on how Black plays. } ) ( { After } 11.Kb1 { , Black has a wide choice. We can't cover every move, so we'll speak about the three most popular moves: } 11...Qe7 { , } { 11...Ne5 and 11...Bxe3 .

Also, a quick note! Sometimes Black plays 11...Bxb3? but it's a big mistake to gift us the bishop pair. You can recapture with either pawn with a big advantage and simple play. } ) Qe7 } 
12. g4! ( { Now that the queen has stepped off of d8, Black is already threatening } 12.-- d5! { so we have to be careful. This kind of move will typically at least equalize for Black since, if you notice, we have more space, but we're actually less developed than Black (all of their minor pieces are out of their starting squares, while we have a bishop still stuck on f1). So, we need to be careful! } { Again, 11...Bxe3 is very similar to previous instances of ...Bxe3 positions already examined. For instance, after 12.Qxe3 a5 13.a3 the position differs from this line [/variation/28221305/#/13/w] covered via @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2ppp/1bnp1n2/8/4P3/1NN1B3/PPP1QPPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@ 8...Bxe3?! move order only very slightly (here our king is on b1 while in the other position, it was on c1 and our pawn was on g4). This difference doesn't change the evaluation in any significant way. } ) Ne5!? } ( { This move not only helps us to do what we usually want to do (attack!) but it also puts a tactical stop to Black's threat of } 12...d5 { . You'll face a bunch of different plans from Black here. The three most popular are: } { 12...Rad8 looking for a ...d5 pawn break. } { 12...Ne5 looking to pressure our kingside pawns and threaten some tricky piece sacrifices. } { 12...Nd7 anticipating g4-g5 and looking to generate piece play on the queenside. } ) { With this tricky move Black is actually threatening to capture on g4 where they will win a lot of pawns and a rook for two minor pieces, a deal that may even leave them winning. So we must be careful about this plan. } 
13. Bc1! { We play the same move as against 12...Rad8. [/variation/28221313/#/13/w] Here this move uses subtle tactical means to deal with the threat. White is doing really well here, and unless Black captures on g4, then we can just continue with normal moves like 14.Nd4 or 14.h4 and continue to build up our position. So the only thing we will focus on is to show how White ends up with a winning position if Black sacrifices on g4. } Nexg4? 
14. fxg4  is that here Black has kept their f6-knight, which presses e4. But we have one very clever tactic at our disposal! } 
15. Nd5! } { This beautiful counter-attacking move solves all of White's problems! It's a really important move to remember as it leaves us practically winning, while all other moves offer equality at best. } Bxe2 ( { Black has nothing better than to trade queens. } 15...Qe6? 16.Nxf6+ gxf6 { to keep the bishop protected, but } 17.Qg2!+- { Black's light-squared bishop is pinned, and so we don't even let them capture our rook on d1. White is up a piece. } ) 
16. Nxe7+ Rxe7 
17. Bxe2 Nxe4 
18. Bf3! } { A beautiful move. Black has three pawns for the piece, but our piece is much more powerful on this board because we have attacking chances and the bishop pair. } Nf2? } { It's important to note that Black can't win an exchange this way. } 
19. Rde1 $16  } ( { Or } 19.Rhe1 { . White leverages Black's undefended rook to avoid material losses. In case you are uncertain as to why the position after 18.Bf3! is much better for White in spite of an approximate material balance, I would recommend playing it against a training partner or analysing it further by yourself using a strong engine. } ) *

