[Event "Starting Out: The Scotch"]
[White "14) Schmidt Variation 4...Nf6 - Sidelines"]
[Black "Schmidt Variation 4...Nf6 5.Nxc6 dxc6 #1"]
[Date "2023.07.18"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C45"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/28221317"]

1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 exd4 
4. Nxd4 Nf6 { Black goes for the Schmidt Variation. This is one of Black's most solid and principled systems against the Scotch. They develop the knight to its most natural square and, at the same time, threaten to take our e4-pawn. }
5. Nxc6 } ( { From here, we can play } 5.Nc3 { taking the game into what is known as the Scotch Four Knights Game, or we can play the more forcing 5.Nxc6.

In this repertoire, we're going to be recommending } ) ( 5.Nxc6 { . The reason for this is because while } ) ( 5.Nc3 { often transposes, if we choose this move order, we would also be allowing the tricky } 5...Nxe4!? { when the point is that after } 6.Nxe4 Qe7! { Black will recover their piece. White is not worse here, but the lines get very complicated, so it makes sense to avoid this possibility. } ) dxc6?! ( { White damages Black's structure, though admittedly, after the common response of } 5...bxc6 { , Black will get some benefits in exchange. These are a greater central pawn presence and the semi-open b-file, where they will often end up placing a rook. } ) { This is a move we should welcome since Black voluntarily allows us to take away their castling rights. } 
6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 
7. f3 ( { Another good move in this position would be the natural move } 7.Nc3 { , but I prefer this way of defending the pawn since, as we see in the 7...Bc5 line, [/variation/28221318/#/7/b] we will sometimes prefer to develop our queen’s knight via a different square than c3. } )Be6 { Black now mostly chooses between either 7...Bc5 or 7...Be6 , depending on which diagonal they think is most important to control first. } { A lot of the time, Black will post their bishop on e6. Here I recommend a funny-looking plan based on going hunting after this strong piece. } 
8. Nc3 Bc5 
9. Ne2! { We are able to get away with playing a lot of manoeuvring moves before completing our development because of the absence of queens and the fact that our centre is very stable, so our king remains safe on e1. } Ke7 { Sooner or later, Black will likely correct their king's placement. } 
10. Nf4 $16  } { Next, we will capture the bishop (unless Black retreats it, but then we would have 11.Bc4 taking over the good diagonal with our own bishop). White will have an enduring edge based on the better pawn structure and the bishop pair. } *

