8. exd5 cxd5 ( { This is the main line. Black regains the pawn immediately and takes away some unusual options for White, like } 8...O-O 9.dxc6 { . } ) 
9. O-O } O-O ( { Black can also start with } 9...c6 { but after } 10.h3 O-O { , we reach the same position. } ) 
10. h3!? } h6 ( { White covers the g4-square and prepares to place the queen on the f3-square in the near future without having to worry about being harassed by moves like ...Bg4. This position is quite flexible, so Black has tried many moves here. We'll consider the two that are by far most popular: } 10...c6 { and } ) ( 10...h6 { .

An important note is that here it's more important to familiarize oneself with a collection of ideas rather than focus on rote memorization. The reason for this is that it's a flexible position (making it impossible to have pre-learned replies to everything Black might do) while the pawn structure is fairly fixed (meaning that a lot of the plans will arise time and time again, even if the specific position is slightly different to the ones covered in this course).

To make the point more general, this may be a good time to comment that one of the things that professional chess players are very good at doing is knowing when to use their limited time and energy to memorize specific lines, and when they are instead better served focusing on building a general understanding of the position. This position is an example of one where the latter approach works best. } { 10.Bg5 This has traditionally been the most popular approach from White, but over time Black has shown that the pin is not too uncomfortable. Sometimes White will even follow up with 11.Qf3 and Black will allow their pawn structure to be ruined on f6. However, Black will emerge with better central control and the bishop pair, which practice has shown offsets White's superior structure. For this reason, we'll be adopting a more modern way of playing with 10.h3 . } ) { Often, the Black player will decide to stop the possible pin that would arise if White was allowed to play 11.Bg5 next. This is not a bad move, but also should not worry us too much since, after all, we had the option to play 10.Bg5 earlier but instead chose to play 10.h3 and take the game in a different direction. } ( 10...Bxc3?! { It's worth quickly commenting that White would be happy to sustain some damage to their pawn structure in order to gain the bishop pair. In particular, with Black's most central pawn being on d5 (a light square), they should be careful to not part ways with their bishop. } 11.bxc3 $16 { White will follow up with moves like 12.Qf3 and 13.Re1. Long-term, White may even be able to undouble their c-pawns by playing c3-c4. } ) 
11. Qf3 { Now that the g4-square is under control, our queen takes up the most active square and at the same time puts pressure on Black's d5-pawn. } Be6 ( 11...c6 { transposes to this line [/variation/28221340/#/11/b] covered via @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/p1p2ppp/5n2/3p4/1b6/2NB3P/PPP2PP1/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 10@@EndFEN@@ 10...c6 move order. } ) 
12. Bf4 { Finishing our minor piece development, bringing the bishop to the most active square available. } c5 { Sometimes Black takes a very aggressive approach in the centre rather than the more usual placement of the c-pawn on c6. } 
13. Rfd1! } ( { It seems strange to play this move and not the more natural-looking } 13.Rad1 { . The reason for this is that by moving our king's rook, we free up the f1-square in case Black pushes their c-pawn in the future and forces our bishop to move. } )Bxc3? { Note that Black cannot play 13...c4 straight away since we would snap it up with 14.Bxc4! } { Usually Black damages our pawn structure here, but it's not a good idea since now we have the bishop pair and we'll also be able to play c3-c4 in the future, undoubling our pawns. } 
14. bxc3 Qe7 ( { Just to show how quickly Black can land themselves in trouble, we'll show why Black's two most popular continuations here ( } 14...Qa5 { and } ) ( 14...Qe7 { ) are big mistakes. } ) ( { This square makes a lot of sense, but Black is in tactical trouble! } 14...Qa5? { Black leaves the knight on f6 undefended, a typical tactic to watch out for in these positions. } 15.Bxh6!+- { White is up a clean pawn with a big attack to boot. Note that } 15...Qxc3? { would lose the queen after } 16.Bh7+! ) 
