12. Bf4 { Finishing our minor piece development, bringing the bishop to the most active square available. } Bd6 { Challenging our bishop on f4 is a very logical idea, and it's the most popular path chosen by Black. Here there's a few ways we can play. I recommend a funky plan of trying to get a bishop versus knight middlegame. } 
13. Nb5!? } } { Forcing Black to exchange on f4. } Bxf4 
14. Qxf4 c5 { Black improves their control of the centre. } 
15. Nc7! } { White is hunting Black's bishop. } Rb8 
16. Nxe6 fxe6 
17. b3 $14  } -- ( { White has a more compact pawn structure and a strong bishop, so we have better chances. Nevertheless, this position is very tricky since Black can drum up some counterplay against our kingside with moves like } 17...Nh5 { , followed by ...Nf4 and ...Qg5, so it is definitely a position worth analysing further if you are planning to play it against a strong player.

The main thing I would check for is how to best parry the attack (the short answer is by placing our light-squared bishop on f1 and our queen on g3!). } )
