To make the point more general, this may be a good time to comment that one of the things that professional chess players are very good at doing is knowing when to use their limited time and energy to memorize specific lines, and when they are instead better served focusing on building a general understanding of the position. This position is an example of one where the latter approach works best. } { 10.Bg5 This has traditionally been the most popular approach from White, but over time Black has shown that the pin is not too uncomfortable. Sometimes White will even follow up with 11.Qf3 and Black will allow their pawn structure to be ruined on f6. However, Black will emerge with better central control and the bishop pair, which practice has shown offsets White's superior structure. For this reason, we'll be adopting a more modern way of playing with 10.h3 . } ) 
11. Qf3 { The logical follow-up. This is the most active square for the queen, from where it puts pressure on Black's central pawns and supports the bishop on f4 in many lines. } Bd6 
12. Bf4! ( { Sometimes Black anticipates } 12.Bf4 { and decides to plant their bishop there straight away. We can continue with our same plan. } ) ( { This is the idea behind our setup with the queen on f3. Rather than trying to make something of the pin after } 12.Bg5 { , we are focused on exchanging Black's dark-squared bishop and trying to exploit their somewhat weakened structure over the long run. Given that their central pawns are on light squares, it should work to our advantage to exchange their dark-squared bishop, as we can hope to be left with a good vs bad minor piece situation on the board. } ) Rb8 { This is most popular here, again a typical idea with Black seeking to make use of their semi-open b-file. } 
13. b3 { Shutting down activity and keeping our pawn structure harmonious. } Rb4 } { This is the most popular move, and it makes sense because Black figures that it's a more active and promising idea to target our } { f4 bishop with the rook than with { 13...Qc7 . There's nothing terribly wrong about Black capturing 13...Bxf4 . It's just that they usually avoid it because they don't want our queen to be in control of the h2-b8 diagonal after 14.Qxf4 $14 . } 
14. Ne2!  we return to this idea of supporting our bishop on f4. } Re8 { Black, as is usually the case, steps their rook onto the e-file to generate some activity. } 
15. c4! { Same plan as usual! White puts Black's centre under pressure, and, in some instances, we may leave them with an isolated pawn. } Ne4?! { Another try from Black has been this move. Optically it's appealing as Black is using their outpost on e4 to centralize their knight. But in fact, here we can get a good vs bad minor piece position on the board. } 
16. Bxe4 } dxe4 } ( { Forced, but not ideal. Black's structure on the queenside has worsened now that c6 becomes an isolated pawn. Additionally, White is much better prepared to make use of the newly opened d-file. } 16...Rxe4? 17.Rfd1 { Black is completely tangled up, with threats for White, including } 17...-- 18.Bxd6 Qxd6 19.Qxe4! { capitalizing on the pin. } ) 
17. Qg3 Bxf4 
18. Nxf4 } { White has a better structure, and Black's bishop is not such a good piece because all of their central pawns are on light squares. } *

