1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 exd4 
4. Nxd4 Bb4+ 
5. c3!  that we go for against the Schmidt Variation 4...Nf6. } { That said, I believe 5.c3 to be the strongest response to 4...Bb4+, so that is what we're covering here. } ) { If any Black player does this against you, it's usually an indication that they haven't studied the variation and are just assuming that there is value in keeping the c3-pawn pinned to the king. But in fact, the bishop here is just very poorly placed and we can put it under a lot of pressure. } 
6. Nxc6! { First, we resolve the tension between the knights, before going after Black's dark-squared bishop. } bxc6 ( { If } 6...dxc6 { you should exchange queens and follow the same plan as here after that. } ) 
7. a4! } { Threatening to win a piece with 8.b4 and 9.a5. } a6 { Black has to find a way to save their bishop. } 
8. Nd2 Bb6 ( { White now threatens } 8...-- 9.Nc4 { when after } 9...Bb6 10.Nxb6! { Black won't be able to capture back with the a-pawn as they would desire (recapturing towards the centre) since they just played ...a6 on their last move. This is a subtle positional idea behind provoking 7...a6 with our move 7.a4. } ) 
9. Nc4 } { If Black lets us, we'll capture their bishop and the combination of our bishop pair, better central control, and their vulnerable queenside pawn structure will add up to giving us a near-winning advantage. } Ba7 
10. Bd3 $16  } { White has a big advantage as Black has wasted too much time moving their dark-squared bishop around. At the same time, their pawn structure is compromised and we have a better grip on the centre. We'll play 11.O-O next and at some point may wish to push our pawn to e5 to cramp Black, depending on what they do. } *

[Event "Starting Out: The Scotch"]
[White "17) Malaniuk Variation 4...Bb4+ - Introduction"]
[Black "Malaniuk Variation 4...Bb4+ 5.c3 Be7 #1"]
[Date "2023.07.18"]
