[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/28221351"]

1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 exd4 
4. Nxd4 Bb4+ 
5. c3! ( { This is known as the Malaniuk Variation. It's not something you're going to encounter often at the club level, though, probably because the idea is a little unintuitive. So what is the idea? Well, Black gives the check to provoke White into playing } 5.c3 { . After this, White won't have access to this square with their knight. } { So, for example, against the Classical Variation 4...Bc5 , we set ourselves up with our knights on b3 and c3, respectively. But against the Malaniuk, we need to change our plans because the c3-square is occupied by our pawn. In essence, Black is trying to frustrate our piece harmony with this early bishop check! } ) Be7 ( { We're going to be obliging them. As we will see, we can find good plans against all of Black's options from here on out and at the end of the day. It's just too valuable to be able to block the check 'with tempo' (meaning that they have to move their bishop again). } 5...Nxd4? { Black presents us with a choice of which piece to capture. } 6.cxb4! $16 { The bishop pair, more space and a lead in development far outweigh a slightly damaged pawn structure. Black now has to spend more time moving their knight around, while we have easy, developing moves to look forward to. White stands much better. } { Nc3 and Bc4 is easy development. } { 5.Nc3!? If, at some point, you wish to expand upon this repertoire, you can take a look at this alternative. What's interesting about it is that objectively speaking, Black has nothing better than 5...Nf6 when after 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.Bd3 d5 , we are playing the same system [/variation/28221338/#/7/b] that we go for against the Schmidt Variation 4...Nf6. } { That said, I believe 5.c3 to be the strongest response to 4...Bb4+, so that is what we're covering here. } ) ( { In classical time controls, this has been the second most popular line. It's a much better placement of the bishop than either } 5...Bd6 { or } ) ( 5...Ba5 { , but it still allows us to play a strong idea. } ) 
6. Nf5! } } { Targeting both the bishop and the g7-pawn. } Bf8 ( { This is almost never played but is objectively similar in value to } 6...Bf6 { . } ) 
7. c4!? } { The Maroczy bind is characterized by pawns on c4 and e4 and is named after Hungarian Grandmaster Geza Maroczy, who was one of the world's best players in the early 20th century. The main purpose of this bind is to establish a vice-like grip over the d5-square and to use the space advantage to squeeze the opponent in the middlegame. } d6 
8. Nc3 g6 ( { It's a better idea for Black to evict our knight than to give us the bishop pair by playing } 8...Bxf5?! ) 
9. Ne3 } { Since White's strategy revolves around controlling the d5-square, this move makes a lot of sense to me. } Bg7 
10. Ned5 $16  -- ( { We'll leave our analysis here as White has built up a nice advantage, and the game will soon reach the middlegame stage, but this is definitely a fun variation to study further for those who wish to do so. It's worth noting that Black can easily go wrong here.

For example, a natural move like } 10...Nge7 { leads to a lot of discomforts after } 11.Bg5 { with an annoying pin. It's simply not so easy for Black to find a good plan with a lack of space and weak dark squares! } )
*

