4. Nxd4 Bb4+ 
5. c3! ( { This is known as the Malaniuk Variation. It's not something you're going to encounter often at the club level, though, probably because the idea is a little unintuitive. So what is the idea? Well, Black gives the check to provoke White into playing } 5.c3 { . After this, White won't have access to this square with their knight. } { So, for example, against the Classical Variation 4...Bc5 , we set ourselves up with our knights on b3 and c3, respectively. But against the Malaniuk, we need to change our plans because the c3-square is occupied by our pawn. In essence, Black is trying to frustrate our piece harmony with this early bishop check! } ) Bd6?! ( { We're going to be obliging them. As we will see, we can find good plans against all of Black's options from here on out and at the end of the day. It's just too valuable to be able to block the check 'with tempo' (meaning that they have to move their bishop again). } 5...Nxd4? { Black presents us with a choice of which piece to capture. } 6.cxb4! $16 { The bishop pair, more space and a lead in development far outweigh a slightly damaged pawn structure. Black now has to spend more time moving their knight around, while we have easy, developing moves to look forward to. White stands much better. } { Nc3 and Bc4 is easy development. } { 5.Nc3!? If, at some point, you wish to expand upon this repertoire, you can take a look at this alternative. What's interesting about it is that objectively speaking, Black has nothing better than 5...Nf6 when after 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.Bd3 d5 , we are playing the same system [/variation/28221338/#/7/b] that we go for against the Schmidt Variation 4...Nf6. } { That said, I believe 5.c3 to be the strongest response to 4...Bb4+, so that is what we're covering here. } ) ( { This square doesn't seem very inspiring! Black blocks their d7-pawn with no real upside versus, for instance, } 5...Be7 { or the main line of } ) ( 5...Bc5 { . } ) 
6. Bd3 } Nf6? ( { Simple development makes sense to me. Plus, what's cool about this move is that looking at the database I noticed most of the time Black continues with either } 6...Nxd4 { or } ) ( 6...Nf6 { , both of which are mistakes. Always nice to play lines that invite our opponents to go wrong early! } ) { This move seems really natural, but actually White has a clever way of posing some serious problems immediately. } 
7. Nf5! } { Targeting d6 and g7. } Bf8 { This is the only way for Black to stop the dual threats of Nxd6 and Nxg7+. } 
8. e5! { The clever point. We force Black to waste more time moving their minor pieces around while we have grabbed a whole bunch of space in the centre. } Nxe5? { Black cannot play this. } 
9. Qe2 d6 
10. f4+- } { And White wins a piece. } *

