1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 exd4 
4. Nxd4 Bb4+ 
5. c3! ( { This is known as the Malaniuk Variation. It's not something you're going to encounter often at the club level, though, probably because the idea is a little unintuitive. So what is the idea? Well, Black gives the check to provoke White into playing } 5.c3 { . After this, White won't have access to this square with their knight. } { So, for example, against the Classical Variation 4...Bc5 , we set ourselves up with our knights on b3 and c3, respectively. But against the Malaniuk, we need to change our plans because the c3-square is occupied by our pawn. In essence, Black is trying to frustrate our piece harmony with this early bishop check! } ) Bc5  with the only difference being that here Black has coaxed us into putting our pawn on c3 instead of c2. This forces us to change our approach to the opening since we can't go for any plans that involve a quick Nb1-c3. } 
6. Be3 } Qf6?! ( { Developing, supporting the knight on d4, and creating the threat of } 6...-- 7.Nxc6 { which would win a piece. } ) { Sometimes Black slots the queen out to f6 with the intention of pressuring our knight on d4 and developing their knight to e7. I think this system doesn't make too much sense in the Malaniuk Variation as Black has coaxed us into playing c2-c3 earlier, so our knight on d4 is well defended. } 
7. g3 } } { We can play in a few different ways against this system, but I like going for a fianchetto approach for a couple of reasons. One is that we will exert strong control over the d5-square. The second is that against a queen on f6 we may wish to play f2-f4 in the future. In this case our pawn on g3 is helpful. } Nge7 
8. Bg2 O-O 
9. O-O d6 { Black usually continues in this fashion, but it allows us to damage their pawn structure. } 
10. Nxc6! { This is the simplest way of getting an advantage. } Nxc6 
11. Bxc5 { The point of our previous move. Now Black's structure will be damaged. } dxc5 
12. f4 $16  } { White has a clear edge and easy play, since we will soon push our pawn to e5 activating our bishop. Black's doubled pawns on the queenside are a long-term problem. } *

