1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 exd4 
4. Nxd4 Bb4+ 
5. c3! ( { This is known as the Malaniuk Variation. It's not something you're going to encounter often at the club level, though, probably because the idea is a little unintuitive. So what is the idea? Well, Black gives the check to provoke White into playing } 5.c3 { . After this, White won't have access to this square with their knight. } { So, for example, against the Classical Variation 4...Bc5 , we set ourselves up with our knights on b3 and c3, respectively. But against the Malaniuk, we need to change our plans because the c3-square is occupied by our pawn. In essence, Black is trying to frustrate our piece harmony with this early bishop check! } ) Bc5  with the only difference being that here Black has coaxed us into putting our pawn on c3 instead of c2. This forces us to change our approach to the opening since we can't go for any plans that involve a quick Nb1-c3. } 
6. Be3 } Bb6 ( { Developing, supporting the knight on d4, and creating the threat of } 6...-- 7.Nxc6 { which would win a piece. } ) { This is the move you will see almost always as you progress up the levels, though there's a lot more variety at the beginner and club level. By playing this move Black has parried our threat of winning a piece by taking on c6. } ( 6...Nxd4?! { Oftentimes, Black gets impatient and takes our knight. But this allows us to improve our structure. } 7.cxd4! $16 { There's not much to discuss here, as White's next moves are very simple whether Black plays } 7...Bb6 { or } { 7...Bb4+ . We'll develop our knight to c3, our bishop to either d3 or c4, and castle. White has a very pleasant middlegame ahead with such a strong grip on the centre. } ) 
7. Nf5! }  we'll cover the historical main line of 7...Bxe3 , which in my view leads to very comfortable play for White with the game taking on a more positional character. } )
*

