The only trick we have to avoid is @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/2P1P2q/4N3/PP4PP/RN1QKB1R w KQ - 1 12@@EndFEN@@ 12.g3? Qxe4 when suddenly our knight on e3 and our rook on h1 are both hanging. } ) 
11. Nc3 Be6 ( { The knight occupies the best square, and we add even more control over d5. Let's take a look at Black's most popular continuations. These are } 11...Nd7 { , } ) ( 11...Re8 { , and } ) ( 11...Be6 { . } ) 
12. Qd2 } } { Same as in the other lines, our queen goes towards the d2-square from where we bolster our control of the dark squares and support our knight on e3. } a6 { In this line, I'll show one funky positional manoeuvre that Black has sometimes gone for. } 
13. Be2 Qb8 } { This is a famous manoeuvre that can be traced back to old classics such as Janowski - Rubinstein, Karlsbad 1907 when Black played 30...Qb8. Black's idea is to activate their queen via a7. } 
14. O-O { That said, it doesn't especially worry us here. Black's improvement of their queen does not take away the real problem for them, which is their lack of space. } Qa7 
15. Rad1 } b5 ( { This is a nice touch, to take away any } 15...Qd4 { or } ) ( 15...Nd4 { possibilities. Black remains frustrated because they cannot live indefinitely with a big space disadvantage and so many pieces on the board. } ) { Modern engines suggest this as Black's best try, and you can probably expect some frustrated opponents to take a shot at muddying the waters. } 
16. Ncd5! } ( 16.cxb5 { also leads to an advantage for White, but this is cleaner. } ) Bxd5 
17. cxd5 $16  { Black's attempt to generate counterplay on the queenside has only led to us getting a better pawn structure. In the future, we can try to create pressure along the semi-open c-file. } *

