[White "19) Malaniuk Variation - Main Line 7...Bxe3"]
[Black "Malaniuk Variation 4...Bb4+ - 7...Bxe3 Main Line #5"]
[Date "2023.07.18"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C45"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/28221372"]

1. e4 e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 exd4 
4. Nxd4 Bb4+ 
5. c3! Bc5 
6. Be3 Bb6 
7. Nf5! Bxe3 } { Now we finally turn our attention to Black's main move. Black is agreeing to exchange bishops since this will attract our knight back to the e3-square, and in this way, Black no longer has to worry about the attack on the g7-pawn. } 
8. Nxe3 } { The good news for us of facing this line, however, is that our knight on e3 does an excellent job of covering the d5-square. And so this line will be less about concrete tactics and more a positional battle where we'll focus on controlling the d5-square and squeezing Black with the space advantage. } Nf6 } { The most principled continuation. Black develops the king's knight to the best square available, and at the same time, targets the pawn on e4. } ( 8...d6 { This is the third most popular move, but it has no independent value as the game will transpose to 8...Nf6 positions. } 9.c4 Nf6 10.Nc3 O-O 11.f3 { We arrive at the same position as we reach in our main line after 11.Nc3. } ) 
9. f3! } { Defending the pawn in the right way. Now we maintain sufficient control over the d5-square so Black is unable to break in the centre. } ( 9.Nd2? { It's important to avoid Black's strategic threat. With a move like this, or 9.Bd3?, we block the control of our queen over the d5-square. } 9...d5!= { Suddenly, Black gets to break in the centre. If we allow Black to rob us of our central advantage, they will quickly equalize. } ) O-O ( { Sometimes Black plays } 9...d6 { instead, but after } 10.c4 O-O { we end up in the same position. } ) 
10. c4! } { Setting up the so-called Maroczy Bind, defined by placing pawns on c4 and e4 in order to clamp down on the d5-square. A second benefit of this move is that we free up the c3-square for our knight to go there next. To be honest, this is just not a good situation for Black. White's play will be relatively straightforward and, as we shall see in the remainder of the chapter, once Black is left with a space disadvantage, all they will be able to do is manoeuvre patiently and hope that we get reckless.

We'll show some brief lines from here on out. Rote memorisation is not effective in such positions as they are very flexible, so the theory quickly becomes limitless. The best way to improve your play in these positions is to train them with a training partner and analyse the games afterwards with a computer. Or, more generally, to study how to play with a space advantage, which is a branch of positional chess. } d6 ( { Black prepares to finish their development. } 10...Nxe4? { Every once in a while an opponent might take a shot at your king in this fashion, but they will not get anywhere near to enough compensation. } 11.fxe4 Qh4+ 12.Kd2 Qxe4 13.Nc3+- { Black only has two pawns for the piece, while our king is very safe since we have many pieces surrounding it.

The only trick we have to avoid is @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pppp1ppp/2n5/8/2P1P2q/4N3/PP4PP/RN1QKB1R w KQ - 1 12@@EndFEN@@ 12.g3? Qxe4 when suddenly our knight on e3 and our rook on h1 are both hanging. } ) 
11. Nc3 Nd7 } ( { The knight occupies the best square, and we add even more control over d5. Let's take a look at Black's most popular continuations. These are } 11...Nd7 { , } ) ( 11...Re8 { , and } ) ( 11...Be6 { . } ) { This knight maneuver has been the most popular move in classical chess. The logic is that since our pawns are primarily on light squares, Black should try to exploit the relatively weak dark squares. Hence the knight is eyeing up a transfer to c5. } 
12. Qd2 } } { Most of the time, we'll play this move. We empty the d1-square for our rook to occupy it in some lines, and at the same time, we're also now defending the knight on e3. } Nc5 
13. Be2 } { Finishing our development. Here Black has only one break available to them. Let's examine its consequences. } f5 { Black typically tries to challenge our central space advantage with this move, but it does leave Black's kingside permanently weak. } 
14. exf5 { We have to capture. Otherwise, after ...fxe4 we would be left with an isolated pawn on e4. } Bxf5 
15. Nxf5! { It's a good idea to win the bishop in this case. Now over the course of the middlegame, our unopposed bishop is going to cause a lot of problems for Black along the weakened light squares. } Rxf5 
16. O-O { The consequence of the break has not been too harmful for us. We still have good central control and we've now got bishop and knight vs two knights, which is a clear advantage on such an open board. } a5 } { You can expect this move a lot of the time, as Black seeks to stabilize their knight on c5 by securing firm control over the b4-square. } 
17. f4! } { This is the last important detail of this position. Not only is it useful to control the e5-square but, more importantly, the bishop on e2 will now come to life. } Kh8 { Black has lots of moves, but you can probably expect this one quite a lot since it's a serious concern for Black to keep their king on the open a2-g8 diagonal. } 
18. Bf3 $16  } { White stands much better. While Black's knights are quite well-placed, they don't have any outposts to advance to. On the other hand, our knight can move to d5 soon while our bishop has become a monster. Meanwhile, Black's king is permanently weakened in the absence of the f7 pawn.

Overall, the main line of the Malaniuk Variation is not as challenging as 7...g6. [/variation/28221362/#/7/b] The important thing to remember is to go for the Maroczy Bind setup and squeeze our opponents with the extra space. Black will often try to break with ...f5 in order to chip away at our space advantage, but this will leave their kingside more vulnerable and sometimes will also lead to us getting bishop + knight vs two knights, which is a favourable imbalance. } *

