1. -- { Welcome to the model games section! Here you'll find a collection of games that I've selected because I felt like they were a great mix of instructive, fun, and motivating (all of the games are White victories) . The games are mostly Grandmaster battles and all of them feature a variation covered in our repertoire, making them especially instructive to students of this course.

For those students who want to make the Scotch a lifetime weapon, I would advise to try to make it a habit of regularly taking a look at high-level games in this opening. The classics are great to give you an idea of the kind of ideas that were popular in the past, and understanding why some of those went out of fashion will help you to deepen your knowledge. The modern games are excellent for catching new trends early and adding some strings to your bow over time.

Fair warning: modern theory at the Grandmaster level can be hard to follow, so I would advise this strategy primarily to 1800+ online rating students of the course, though, if it's fun for you, you can do it at any level. } } *

[Event "Starting Out: The Scotch"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "(1) Michael Adams vs. Jaan Ehlvest, Gibraltar 2013"]
[Date "2023.07.18"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C62"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/28448292"]

1. e4 } e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. Bb5 d6 
4. d4 Bd7 
5. Nc3 exd4 
6. Nxd4 g6 ( { In the course, we covered the two most popular continuations of } 6...Nf6 { here [/variation/28221212/#/6/b] and } ) ( 6...Nxd4 { here. [/variation/28221211/#/6/b] This move, however, is also very logical, as Black seeks to fianchetto their bishop and pressure the knight on d4. } ) 
7. O-O?! ( { Not the most challenging approach. In my view, } 7.Be3! { is a better plan against the fianchetto system. The reason will become clear very soon. } 7...Bg7 8.Qd2 { White sets up the queen-bishop battery. } 8...Nf6 9.Bxc6 { Damaging Black's structure and taking away the possibility of ...Nxd4 for Black. } 9...bxc6 10.Bh6! { This is the point of playing in this way. Black won't get to keep their strong dark-squared bishop. And without it, they will lose the bishop pair as well as some king safety. White is left with a really pleasant middlegame with better central control and pawn structure. } ) Bg7 
8. Bxc6 { GM Adams goes for the damage to the structure. } bxc6 
9. Re1 { Black has the bishop pair, but White has a healthier pawn structure and centralized pieces. } Ne7 
10. Bf4 { White now has the possibility of pushing 11.e5, depending on what Black does. } c5 { Black kicks back White's strong knight. } 
11. Nf3 } { White is again threatening e5, which is very scary for Black since Black's c7-d6-c5 pawn chain can get blown apart very quickly. } f6 { GM Ehlvest takes drastic measures to stop White's threat. } ( { It was better for Black to let White carry out the threat, and go for counterplay with } 11...O-O! { . For instance, } 12.e5 Nf5! 13.exd6 cxd6 14.Bxd6 Nxd6 15.Qxd6 Bg4= { and Black has enough compensation due to the combination of the bishop pair and the queenside pressure, but this is a tough line to evaluate, so it's no surprise that GM Ehlvest went for 11...f6 instead. } ) 
12. Qd2 ( 12.Nd5! { This aggressive move was best. Amazingly, this move stops Black from castling due to a very clever tactical idea: } 12...O-O 13.e5! { Breaking through in the centre. } 13...dxe5 14.Nxe5! { A temporary piece sacrifice. } 14...fxe5 15.Bg5 { The knight on e7 is pinned. } 15...Re8 { Black defends and is ready to sacrifice their rook on e7. } 16.Nxe7+ Rxe7 17.Bxe7 Qxe7 { Black is up two bishops for a rook, which would normally be a winning advantage. But White has one crushing move. } 18.Qd5+! { White wins the rook on a8 on the next move. } ) O-O 
13. Bh6 { White seeks to exchange Black's dark-squared bishop to soften up the kingside. } a5 { Black begins trying to drum up some activity on the queenside. } 
14. h3 { Cutting out ...Bg4 possibilities. } a4 
15. Rad1 { White is ignoring Black's advances on the queenside and instead focusing on improving all the pieces. } Be6? { Black misses White's strong threat after 15.Rad1. } 
16. Bxg7! Kxg7 
17. e5! { White breaks through! } fxe5 ( 17...dxe5 18.Qe3 { White will win the c5-pawn next and is likely to break through with a piece sacrifice on e5 soon after. } ) 
18. Nxe5! { This is White's beautiful idea. Black's minor pieces along the e-file are very unstable. } Qc8 ( 18...dxe5? 19.Qe2 19...Qc8 20.Qxe5+ Rf6 21.Ne4+- { Black's position completely collapses. } ) 
19. Ng4 Ng8 { Black tries to cover the h6-square. } 
20. Ne4 } { Black resigned here. The position is completely hopeless as Qc3+ is coming next, when Black's king will find it impossible to find a safe home. } 1-0

[Event "Starting Out: The Scotch"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "(2) Lukas Cernousek vs. Zbynek Hracek, Ostrava 2019"]
[Date "2023.07.18"]
[Result "1-0"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/28448293"]

1. e4 } e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. Bb5 Nf6 
4. O-O Be7 
5. Nc3 d6 
6. d4 exd4 
7. Nxd4 Bd7 
8. Nxc6 bxc6 
9. Bd3 O-O 
10. f4 Qb8 ( { Up to here, we are following the main line of 'The Passive 3...d6' chapter. [/course/179653/4] In the course, we considered a few moves: } 10...Bg4 { , } ) ( 10...Rb8 { and } ) ( 10...h6?! { . Black here goes for something completely different and pretty unusual. } ) { Since Black is playing along three ranks only, they are trying to find a creative way to activate their queen. } 
11. Qf3 Qb4 
12. Kh1 { This is almost always a useful move in positions where we've pushed our f2-pawn as the g1-a7 diagonal is wide open. } Rab8 { The problem with Black's strategy is that they're not actually threatening much. } 
13. Rb1 ( 13.Bd2! { This would have been the best move, highlighting that all of Black's pressure along the b-file is not effective since the pawn cannot be taken. } 13...Qxb2? 14.e5! { Breaking through with the typical e4-e5 push! } 14...Ng4 15.h3 Nh6 16.f5! { Black is getting steamrolled. } 16...dxe5 17.Bxh6 Qxc3 18.f6+- { This is just a sample line, but you can see the kind of crushing attack that White can quickly strike up. Here Black can resign because there are too many threats: fxe7 and Bxh7+ are two of them. } ) Qa5 
14. Bd2 Qh5 { Black offers the queen exchange. } 
15. Qg3! { Correctly declining the offer, since Black's king is the one at risk of being attacked. } Qh6 
16. Be2?! { Going a little passive with the bishop. Black must have been a little concerned about ...Nh5 or ...Ng4 ideas. } g6 ( { Black plays too passively, a move like } 16...Rb4 { hitting the pawn on e4 would have been a more active try. } ) 
17. b3! { Now White no longer has to worry about babysitting the pawn on b2. } Rfe8 
18. Rbd1! } { Defending the bishop on d2 is useful as it's being x-rayed by Black's queen on h6. So now 19.e5 or 19.f5 ideas start to be possible. } Qg7 
19. h3 { It's usually good to be patient in situations where your opponent lacks space, but here Black can aim for a ...d5 pawn break soon so White should not be overly patient! } ( 19.e5! { The direct move was already possible. } 19...Nd5 20.Nxd5 cxd5 21.Bc3 dxe5 22.Rxd5+- { Black's position is falling apart in the centre. } ) Be6 
20. Qf3 d5! { Black is allowed to be the first to break, though White is still in control of the position. } 
21. e5 ( { Grabbing space. } 21.Bd3! { This may have been stronger here. After all, we can always play 22.e5 on the next move, since Black never wants to play } 21...dxe4? { here because then they'd be left with doubled and isolated pawns on the c-file. } ) Nd7 
22. Be3 f6! { Black correctly targets White's strong central pawn. } 
23. exf6 Bxf6 
24. Na4! } { The c7-c6-d5 pawn formation that we often see in the Schmidt Variation (as well as, like here, in the 3...d6 positions) leaves an outpost on c5. Oftentimes it's going to be good to take advantage of that square. } Bf5 
25. Bd3! { Targeting Black's active bishop. } Bxd3 
26. Rxd3 Nb6? { Black, even though a strong and experienced Grandmaster, gets impatient and plays a bad move. } 
27. Nc5! } ( { The reason why 26...Nb6 was bad is that once White declines the piece exchange, the knight on b6 is completely passive as it has no forward jumps. } 27.Nxb6? { This would throw away White's big advantage by fixing Black's pawn structure. } 27...axb6= { . } ) Qe7 
28. Bg1 ( 28.f5! { I'm not sure what stopped White from breaking through immediately on the kingside. If Black tries to keep things closed down with a move like } 28...g5 { , then White is left with a beautiful outpost for their knight on e6. } ) Qe2 
29. f5! ( { Black succeeds in forcing the queen exchange since a move like } 29.Qg3 { would lose to } 29...Qxf1 { . } ) Qxf3 
30. Rdxf3 gxf5 ( 30...g5 { It would have been best to keep things shut down, but it's understandable that Black didn't want this since now White has the e6-outpost for the knight, as well as a protected passed pawn on f5. } ) 
31. Rg3+! { In spite of the queens being off the board, Black's king is way too unsafe. } Kh8 
32. Rxf5 Bg7 
33. Rf7 Be5 
34. Rg5 Rbd8 
35. Rxc7! { A clever tactical point. } Bxc7 
36. Bd4+ Be5 
37. Bxe5+ Rxe5 
38. Rxe5+- { White is up a clean pawn and also has a better structure and better pieces. The rest is a matter of technique, and White converts smoothly. } Nd7 
39. Nxd7 Rxd7 
40. Re8+ Kg7 
41. Rc8 Rd6 
42. Rc7+ Kf6 
43. Rxh7 Ke5 
44. Rxa7 Kd4 
45. Re7 c5 
46. g4 Kc3 
47. Re2 d4 
48. g5 c4 
49. bxc4 Ra6 
50. Rg2 1-0

[Event "Starting Out: The Scotch"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "(3) Marani Rajendran Venkatesh vs. Mahmood Lodhi, Al Ain 2015"]
[Date "2023.07.18"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C44"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/28448294"]

1. e4 } e5 
2. Nf3 Nc6 
3. d4 Nf6 
4. d5 Ne7 
5. Nxe5 Nxe4 
